ce|province]] of {{PH wikidata|province}}, {{PH wikidata|country}}. According to the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, it has a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people.{{PH census|current}}\n\n==Geography==\n\nEscalante has a total land area of {{convert|19276.303|ha}}. It is located on the northeastern tip of Negros Occidental, facing the island of Cebu.  It is {{convert|49|km}} from San Carlos City and {{convert|95|km}} from [[Bacolod City]], the provincial capital.  It is bounded on the north and west by the city of [[Sagay]], on the south by the town of [[Toboso, Negros Occidental|Toboso]] and on the east by the [[Ta\u00f1on Strait]].\n\nOutside the city center of Escalante, there is a separate region of low rolling hills, especially going to its upland barangays towards Mt. Lunay.  The hill land section is the remnant of past volcanism and probably, represents either dormant volcanic cinder cones or outliers of a once more extensive volcanic formation.  Local residents in the upland barangays of Escalante at the foot of Mt. Lunay testify to period rumblings of a volcano generally believed 'to be dead'. An indicator of the dormant character of Mt. Lunay is the existence to this day of a sulphur spring at its foot.  Often, the slopes of these hills as in Barangay Binaguiohan are quite steep.  However, the steepness of the slope has not stopped Escalantehanons in cultivation of the hillside.\n\n===Coastal environment===\n\nThe diversity of plants in the coastal environment of Escalante is one of the richest in Occidental Negros.  Its coasts comprise two surviving ecosystems: the mangrove, consisting of trees and shrubs that occupies the landward portion of its coastal areas; the seagrass, or grasslike plants, that thrive on it shallow nearshore area.  In a limited coastal zone, remnants of a third ecosystem, coral reef may be found but in residual, degraded form.  The marine waters of Escalante are generally warm throughout the year, except for early mornings of the cool months of December, January and February.  Salinity of its waters is within reasonable amount, at 28-36 parts per thousand.\n\n===Climate===\n[[File:Escalante1.jpg|thumb|Mt. Lunay in Barangay Paitan where The Giant Cross used to stand]]\nThe atmospheric conditions influencing the climate of Escalante as a whole are the same conditions operative in Negros Island. During the summer months (April to December) an air stream is directed from the south. This air current follows a counterclockwise path as it approaches the low-pressure center of the Asian continent, and reaches the Philippines from a southwestern direction as the southwestern monsoon or ''habagat''.  During the period from November to January, Negros has relatively cool weather as the Asian continent cools more rapidly than the surrounding seas, resulting in high-pressure centers leading to winds being deflected in a clockwise fashion.\n\nThis period is known as the northeastern monsoon or ''amihan''. From March to April the northeastern wind system dominates. The cool season in Escalante is from December through March. It is also the time when low tides called ''aya-ay'' prevail, making beachcombing of its shores more pleasurable. The latter part of March through June is when the highest temperatures prevail.  But being largely coastal, Escalante enjoys a constant flow of refreshing sea breeze.\n\n==Barangays==\n\nEscalante City is politically subdivided into 21 [[barangay]]s.  The following table shows its corresponding population, area, and distance from the city proper.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Barangay !! Population (2010)<ref name=NSO10>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov.ph/sites/default/files/attachments/hsd/pressrelease/Western%20Visayas.pdf |title=Total Population by Province, City, Municipality and Barangay: as of August 1, 2015 |work=2010 Census of Population and Housing |publisher=Philippine Statistics Authority |accessdate=8 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115103341/http://www.census.gov.ph/sites/default/files/attachments/hsd/pressrelease/Western%20Visayas.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2012 }}</ref> !! Area (has.) !! Distance from city center (km.)\n|-\n| Alimango  || 5,173  || 919.4498  || 3.00\n|-\n| Balintawak   || 15,893  || 720.9231  || 0.00\n|-\n| Binaguiohan  || 2,455  || 726.2457  || 13.28\n|-\n| Buenavista  || 3,844  || 707.7538  || 16.00\n|-\n| Cervantes  || 2,668  || 431.8238  || 6.62\n|-\n| Dian-ay  || 4,844  || 1,750.5637  || 18.50\n|-\n| Hda. Fe  || 2,542  || 552.9899  || 2.34\n|-\n| Japitan  || 2,689  || 586.7144  || 17.00\n|-\n| Jonobjonob  || 7,957  || 1,405.6326  || 2.08\n|-\n| Langub  || 3,065  || 968.2549  || 13.02\n|-\n| Libertad  || 2,604  || 1,839.4097  || 11.72\n|-\n| Mabini  || 7,625  || 1,916.3276  || 7.60\n|-\n| Magsaysay  || 1,502  || 527.0559  || 14.28\n|-\n| Malasibog  || 2,850  || 675.0577  || 7.34\n|-\n| Old Poblacion  || 11,304  || 572.8795  || 6.24\n|-\n| Paitan  || 1,638  || 588.6619  || 13.72\n|-\n| Pinapugasan  || 2,824  || 1,129.2686  || 15.14\n|-\n| Rizal  || 2,206  || 439.3418  || 14.58\n|-\n| Tamlang  || 2,417  || 1,041.3441  || 9.32\n|-\n| Udtongan  || 2,174  || 967.4706  || 10.18\n|-\n| Washington || 5,796   || 720.2289  || 5.12\n|-\n! TOTAL  !! 94,070  !! 19,276.3030 !!\n|}\n\n==History==\n\n===Pre-Spanish Era===\nVirtually nothing is known of Escalante during the pre-Hispanic era. But archaeological findings in October 1975 and May 1976 made by a team of Anthropology students led by Professor Lionel Chiong of Silliman University reveal an early record of men who inhabited not only the present city but also the island of Negros during the pre-Spanish time. The findings were recovered in nine (9) graves in what seemed to be an ancient burial ground in Barangay Japitan, a coastal barangay lying along the Ta\u00f1on Strait, facing the island of Cebu, some 17 kilometers from the city proper.  The artifacts consisted of celadon plate and bowls, stoneware bowls and jars, a Sung Dynasty (960-1280 A.D.) jarlet, gold beads, iron implements, daggers and a hunting knife with an ivory bone handle.\n\nObviously buried with the dead, the plate, bowls, jars and iron implements were found alongside the skeletal remains, the daggers and hunting knives on top of the breast section and the gold beads inside the skulls in-between the upper and lower jaws. When carbon-14 tested, these findings together with the human skeletal remains were found to date as far back as the 12th century A.D. All this proved that present-day Escalante was inhabited by settlers with a relatively developed culture who were engaged in some form of trade and commerce with the outside world, such as the Chinese and Japanese traders who could have brought the jarlet, stoneware and celadon pieces during the Ages of Contacts and Trade with the East (11th & 12th centuries A.D.)\n\n===Spanish Era===\nThe northeastern part of Negros Island was \"one of the most cultivated regions\" in the mid-19th century.\n\nOn November 28, 1856, Governor-General Manuel Crespo issued a decree creating the towns of Escalante and Saravia. The decree ordered \"that the two towns in question would be separated immediately from their mother town, Silay,\" although the spiritual separation of the two \"would await the building of churches and convents in Saravia and Escalante.\"  The latter had its seat of government in the barrio of Nueva Sevilla (Barangay Old Poblacion).<ref>History of Negros by Angel Martinez Cuesta. trans. from original Spanish by Alfonso Felix Jr., and Caritas Sevilla. Historical Conservation Society, Manila: 1980</ref>\n\nThe Parish of Escalante was finally established on May 22, 1860 with Fr. Cipriano Navarro, OAR, as the first Parish Priest.  Fr. Navarro, in a report to the Recollect Provincial in 1861, wrote that the inhabitants of his Parish and its 14 barrios lying along the northeast portion of the island from Calatrava to Himogaan, \"speak the Cebuano dialect and all, or the majority, came from Cebu, with the exception of those from Barrio Marianas (Himogaan) . . . who came from the district of Iloilo and speak the Hiligaynon dialect.\"\n\nIn 1859, a politico-Military Command was established in Bacolod under Governor Emilio E. Saravia with six towns under its jurisdiction: Escalante, Guihulngan, Jinuboan, Jimalalud, Tayasan, and Ayungon.<ref>http://www.cbcponline.net/dumaguete</ref> Two more were added, Arguelles (Sagay) and Calatrava when these were created into separate towns on July 3, 1863.  This ended with the division of Negros into two provinces in 1889.\n\nSchools for boys and girls were established in the late 1860s.  By 1869 a school for boys and another for girls were already operating in the town.  By 1890, these schools were among the very few managed by Normal School graduates.\n\nAs early as 1871, Escalante was a major link between Bacolod and Cebu.  A mail service route, Bacolod-Escalante-Tutuban-Toledo, Cebu was already exclusively in use by May 1871.  In 1875 a mail boat belonging to Emerenciano Amante, the Gobernadorcillo (Mayor) of Escalante, transported mail between Toledo and Escalante every week.\n\nA telegraphic station was established in 1894. The telegraphic cable was extended later on to Tuburan, Cebu and was operational by October 1897.\n\nThe inhabitants of the town lived from subsistence agriculture.  They produced among others, rice, corn, buri, edible root crops, and tobacco. Their second most important economic activity was fishing.\n\nTobacco was grown commercially but its production decreased when monopoly was established starting from the time of Don Emilio Saravia (1855\u20131857), the first politico-military of the Negros Island.  In its stead, sugarcane was gradually being grown. It was not clear when the first sugar mill was established in town. But by 1891, Escalante had already 6 steam-engine sugar mills; 36 powered by horses; and 11 by carabaos. Approximately 848 hectares were planted to sugarcane..\n\n===American Era===\nThe American period covering some 45 years (December, 1898 to July 3, 1946, except for a few years under the Japanese occupation) saw marked changes in the socio-cultural, economic and political complexion of the area and its people. To capture the hearts and minds of the inhabitants without the use of guns and cannons, the Americans opened the first free elementary school at Old Poblacion in the early 1900s.\n\nA Gabaldon-type elementary school building was constructed at Old Poblacion during the term of Mayor Fernando Lucot (1912\u20131918). The municipal hall and the town plaza were constructed and developed during the time of Francisco Ferrer, Sr. Also at this time, the first municipal school site where the first elementary school was located, was formally acquired, and the installation of the Rizal Monument at the public plaza completed.  The municipal portal and Rizal Monument was built on Sept. 15, 1955.  The bandstand and skating rink was constructed on September 28, 1935.\n\n===Japanese Era===\n\nIn 1942, the occupation by the Japanese Imperial forces entered the towns in Escalante. The establishment of the general headquarters of the Philippine Commonwealth Army was active on January 3, 1942 to June 30, 1946 and the 7th Infantry Regiment of the Philippine Constabulary was active again on October 28, 1944 to June 30, 1946 and military stationed in the town municipality of Escalante during the Japanese Occupation.\n\nIn 1945, local Filipino soldiers of the 7th, 72nd, 75th and 76th Infantry Division of the Philippine Commonwealth Army and the 7th Constabulary Regiment of the Philippine Constabulary was liberated the towns in Escalante, Negros Occidental and helping Negrosanon guerrilla fighters defeats and attacking Japanese Imperial forces and ended of the Second World War.\n\nIn 1941, Victor Bedonia succeeded Francisco Ferrer Sr. as mayor, and was supported by the local guerillas. The siege of all Filipino troops of the Philippine Army and Constabulary units was found liberated in the town municipality on 1945 against the Japanese. He served until 1948. The Japanese however installed Enrique Ballesteros as mayor until the end of the war.\n\n===Post-War Era===\nTwo (2) years after liberation, Escalante was divided into two (2) municipalities.  President Elpidio Quirino issued Executive Order 141 dated May 19, 1948 \"Organizing certain barrios of the Municipality of Escalante, Province of Negros Occidental, into an independent municipality under the name Toboso\", to take effect July 1, 1948.  Victor Bedonia who was then the incumbent mayor of Escalante opted to become the first mayor of the newly created town of Toboso. Pedro Benignos took over until 1950. In 1951, Evaristo Sanz took over and was replaced thereafter by Amando Tambo. It was during Mayor Tambo\u2019s time when the seat of government, by virtue of Executive Order No. 301 issued by President Carlos P. Garcia on May 30, 1958, was transferred from Barangay Old Poblacion to its present site at Barangay Balintawak.\n\nThe first high school, the Escalante National High School, was donated by Manuel A. Lopez in 1946 and established in 1948.  A decade later, in 1961, the Mount Carmel College was established by the Order of the Carmelites.  Aside from the churches in the Municipality of Toboso, in Escalante and in Brgy Old. Poblacion, it also erected the Magdalen Hospital which was run by the Sisters of Julie Postel.  This hospital is now called the Dr. Vicente Gustilo District Hospital, under the management of the Provincial Government.  This placed the new town in an enviable position, not only being a center of higher education and quality medical care in this part of Negros.\n\nThis brought about profound changes in the socio-cultural, economic and political life of the town as it provided the much-needed opportunity for children of poor families in the area to acquire college education.  Other public schools were opened up later on, such that there are now 27 public elementary schools, 6 national public high schools and 3 extension high schools.\n\n===The Martial Law Years===\n\nDuring this time, a modern public market, new municipal building, and the 50,000-gallon reservoir was erected under the mayor Braulio P. Lumayno.  The Martial Law Years was seemingly  quiet.  However, the uneven land distribution, marginal food production, and the excesses of the political system created so much discontent especially in the sugarcane farms.  This was one of the reasons why the BAYAN-led \"Welgang Bayan\" which ended in the [[Escalante massacre]]. Twenty-one rallyists who were determined to paralyze traffic, died on the spot on the streets of Escalante when the militia of then-strongman Congressman Armando Gustilo, who was bent on dispersing the rally, fired their guns on rallyists. This event was one of the important factors for the downfall of the Marcos regime.\n\nWith the installation of Pres. Corazon C. Aquino, Mrs. Evelyn L. Hinolan was selected as OIC Mayor.  Then BAYAN Chairman Rolando Ponsica, who was one of the persecuted during the Martial Law years, easily became the mayor in 1988.\n\n==City Charter for Escalante==\n\nAfter 143 years of existence as a municipality, under the leadership of Mayor Santiago G. Barcelona, Jr., Escalante was now qualified to become a city.  On July 24, 1998, the Sangguniang Bayan of Escalante passed Resolution No. 98-79 \"requesting the  Congressman Julio A. Ledesma IV of the 1st District of Negros Occidental to file a bill in Congress creating / converting the Municipality of Escalante into a new City of Escalante.\"  Six days later, Congressman Ledesma filed House Bill No. 1514 \"An act converting the Municipality of Escalante into a component city to be known as the City of Escalante.\"  In spite of a moratorium on the creation of cities imposed by the Malaca\u00f1ang in 1999.\n\nCongress went ahead with its enactment.  After conducting a public hearing right here in the town on November 27, 1999, Congress passed the substitute bill, House Bill No. 8882, on second reading on December 9, 1999.  More than a week later, it passed the bill on third and final reading.\n\nA similar bill, Senate Bill No. 1786, was filed by Sen. Serge Osme\u00f1a III in the House of the Senate on October 22, 1999. Senate Bill No. 2245 (in substitution of Senate Bill No. 1786) was passed on third and final reading on February 8, 2001, the last session of the 11th Congress.\n\nBoth bills became Republic Act No. 9014, \"An act converting the Municipality of Escalante, Province of Negros Occidental into a component city to be known as the City of Escalante.\"  It was signed into law on February 28, 2001 by President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo, and was ratified in a plebiscite held on March 31, 2001.  Of 14,723 who actually voted, 14,075 voted \"YES\" and only 648 voted \"NO\".<ref>City Planning and Development Office, City of Escalante</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Philippine Census \n| align= none\n| title= Population census of Escalante\n| 1903 = 12192\n| 1918 = 29287\n| 1939 = 60152\n| 1948 = 56846\n| 1960 = 59768\n| 1970 = 52060\n| 1975 = 63969\n| 1980 = 71293\n| 1990 = 72685\n| 1995 = 79928\n| 2000 = 79098\n| 2007 = 92035\n| 2010 = 93725\n| 2015 = 94070\n| 2020 =\n| 2025 =\n| 2030 =\n| footnote= Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\nThe city has grown at a respectably fast rate, averaging 1.63% in the ten years (2000 thru 2010). The May 2010 Census on Population showed that population increased to 93,005 persons. This means that on average that population grew by 1.63% annually since 2000.  This is only about 3.20% of the province\u2019s population which includes Bacolod City or 3.88% without it. At this rate, the city\u2019s population is expected to double by year 2053.\n\nThe average household for 2000 was 4.89 persons per household, which is lower than the 5.0 national, 5.1 regional and the 5.24 provincial averages. NSO estimates there were 92,035 persons in 2007 in 18,644 households.  This means, the average households size increased to 4.94.<ref>Philippine Statistics Authority, PopCen 2007</ref>\n\nAs of December 2009, the average age is 24 years old.<ref>Escalante City Health Office 2009</ref>\n\nEscalante has the highest population density (persons/square kilometer) in 2007, among the provinces's cities at 736.3, second only to the provincial capital, Bacolod City.  The provincial average is 362.1, while the cities average 417.8.<ref>Negros Occidental Socio-Economic Trends 2008</ref>\n\nThe people in the city speak the [[Cebuano language]] (often called Bisaya) closely followed by [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]] (often called Ilonggo). [[Filipino language|Filipino]] and [[English language|English]] are generally understood.\n\n==Local government== \nMelecio J. Yap, Jr. is the current Mayor of the City while Johnny A. Gabriel is the current Vice Mayor of the City.  The City belongs to the 1st Congressional District of Negros Occidental, which is under the Gerardo P. Valmayor, Jr.\n\n===List of former mayors===\nSuccession of mayors from 1901 to present:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*German Carballo                                 1901-1904\n*Juan Infante                                 1905-1906\n*Pelagio Abong                                 1906-1907\n*Vidal Clarin                                   1908\n*Placido Visitacion                         1909-1911\n*Fernando Lucot                                 1912-1918\n*Gabino Gamao                                 1919-1921\n*Francisco Ferrer Sr.                         1922-1931\n*Restituto Dejoras                         1931-1934\n*Francisco Ferrer Sr.                         1934-1941\n*Enrique Ballesteros (Japanese\u2013sponsored) 1941-1944\n*Victor Bedonia (Resistance and Commonwealth Military Movement)         1941-1948\n*Pedro Benignos                                 1948-1951\n*Evaristo Sanz                                 1952-1955\n*Amando Tambo                                 1956-1957\n*Braulio P. Lumayno                         1958-1976\n*Jose Pete Parre\u00f1o                   Nov. 1976 \u2013 Mar. 2, 1980\n*Braulio P. Lumayno                  Mar. 1980 \u2013July 16, 1986\n*Evelyn L. Hinolan                  July 17, 1986 \u2013 Nov. 30, 1987\n*Penny Yanong                          Dec. 1, 1987 \u2013 Feb 2, 1988\n*Rolando P. Ponsica                  Feb. 2, 1988 \u2013 Mar. 25, 1998\n*Eme L. Zamora                          Mar. 26, 1998 \u2013 June 30, 1998\n*Santiago G. Barcelona, Jr.          July 1, 1998 \u2013 June 30, 2007\n*Melecio J. Yap, Jr.                   July 1, 2007 \u2013 June 30, 2016\n*Eddie M. Montero                     July 1, 2016 \u2013 June 30, 2019\n*Melecio J. Yap, Jr.                   July 1, 2019 \u2013 present\n}}\n\n==Some notable Escalantehanons==\n*[[James Yap]]\n*[[Ernesto de la Merced II]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.escalantecity.gov.ph Escalante City Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120413163013/http://www.nscb.gov.ph/activestats/psgc/default.asp Philippine Standard Geographic Code]\n*[http://www.blgs.gov.ph/lgpmsv2/cmshome/index.php?pageID=23&frmIdDcfCode=7&fLguType=CM&frmIdRegion=9&frmIdProvince=55&frmIdLgu=974 Local Governance Performance Management System]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Escalante\n| North     = [[Sagay, Negros Occidental|Sagay]]\n| Northeast = ''[[Visayan Sea]]''\n| East      = ''[[Ta\u00f1on Strait]]''\n| South     = [[Toboso, Negros Occidental|Toboso]]\n| West      = [[Sagay, Negros Occidental|Sagay]]\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles Related to Escalante, Negros Occidental\n| list  =\n{{Negros Occidental}}\n{{Philippine cities}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Negros Occidental]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1856]]\n[[Category:1856 establishments in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "RepublicaNegrense", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escalante,_Negros_Occidental"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School", "text_new": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 \n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/old-boys-want-doon-to-stay-as-it-is/cid/473019|title=Old boys want Doon to stay as it is|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October, 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/climb-every-mountain/article28515581.ece |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> \n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nThe annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys should leave The Doon School as members of an aristocracy, but it must be an aristocracy of service inspired by the ideals of unselfishness, not one of privilege, wealth or position\".<ref>''The Doon School Sixty Years On'', 1936, p.4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Lt.-Col.-Eric-Joseph-Simeon-dead/article14764255.ece |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms|title=Ramchandani: Old Boy and \u2018workaholic\u2019 headmaster who transformed Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon Cabinet\"<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /> or \"Dosco Mafia\",<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaster, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person, and the events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President of India [[Pratibha Patil]], King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan, and [[Kapil Sibal]], then minister of [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/dame-dilemma-for-doon-president-s-co-ed-suggestion-evokes-mixed-reaction/cid/473014 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, labelling the bullying scenes \"defamatory\", and obtained a court order to delay its release. The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-film-fallout/articleshow/6941433.cms|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Ex-students-film-celebrating-Doon-draws-schools-ire/articleshow/7159525.cms|title=Ex-student's film 'celebrating' Doon draws school's ire &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India]]n states.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Governance and organisation==\n\nThe school is owned by the [[non-profit]] entity Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which was registered by S.R. Das in 1928 with the aim of establishing public schools in India. Under the IPSS, the Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref> The current board comprises thirteen members and is chaired by [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], an alumnus. The president of [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]] has a seat on the board to represent the views and interests of the alumni.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> At the intramural level, the School Council, comprising the headmaster, heads of department, staff and student representatives from each house, is responsible for legislating and discussing school policies. Every house holds a vote to send four student representatives to the council. Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/class-up-at-doon/230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students at the start of the year by voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>   \n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Those who have a family history with a particular house are assigned to the same house. All houses have rooms, dormitories, kitchen, library, study rooms, and a Common Room for recreation.\n\n===Fees and financial aid===\nAs of April 2020, the annual school fees for Indian students was {{Indian Rupee}}10,25,000, and {{Indian Rupee}}12,81,000 for foreign nationals or [[non-resident Indians]]. Once admission is secured after passing the entrance examination and interview, a student can apply for around 25 scholarships or awards on offer. Some are reserved for boys proficient in sports or arts, and those from an [[Indian Armed Forces|armed forces]] background. The monetary value of financial aid ranges from fifty percent of the tuition fee to being fully funded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/admissions/scholarships/|title=Scholarship Programme Offered by The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> In the media, the school has been described as a \"grooming ground for India's wealthy kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> The last headmaster, Matthew Raggett, has stated that over 25% of Doon's students receive needs-based bursaries, and the school is working towards a completely [[need-blind admission|needs-blind admission]] policy.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. The buildings on campus include the Main Building, housing offices and classrooms, structures for sports facilities, science blocks, music school, library, arts and media centre, auditorium, amphitheatre, dining hall, wellness centre, recycling and waste-treatment plants, and masters' residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412|title=Premium schools &#124; Outlook Business|website=www.outlookbusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]]. A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/doon-school-s-etp-may-be-trendsetter-111031400040_1.html |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Main Building corridor at Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Ground-floor corridor of the school's Main Building, which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Chhota-Hazri-bell-tolls-for-desi-Etons/articleshow/764209.cms |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On Sundays, boys are free to pursue any activity or sport, or go into town for leisure.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\" /> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. The autumn term runs from August to the year-end final examinations in November, after which the boys are promoted to the new class in February.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Each term has a \"test week\" and end-of-term examinations known as \"trials\". Boys meet their tutors every week to discuss any matter, and are able to visit teachers, most of whom live on campus, for further academic help. Subjects on offer include geography, economics, environmental studies, art and design, psychology, music, English, Hindi, Sanskrit, and [[STEM subjects]]. Doon's foreign language offerings include French, German and Spanish. There is a career's department that offers pupils guidance on career paths, college applications, and entrance exams like the [[SAT]]. In recent years, boys have increasingly chosen foreign universities over Indian colleges, sometimes due to the hyper-competitiveness of the [[Higher education in India|Indian higher education system]] that calls for extremely high school-leaving scores for admissions.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/education/it-is-an-elite-school-not-elitist/article23029951.ece|title=\u2018It is an elite school, not elitist\u2019|first=Jaideep Deo|last=Bhanj|date=11 March 2018|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref> Social work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/|title=F.C. Barcelona at Doon - July 2013|date=20 September 2013|website=Doon School}}</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://educationworld.in//EWIssue.aspx|title=India's best boys boarding school|website=EducationWorld.in}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m), during its first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the open-air theatre, Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/raga-meets-rhythm/article28369860.ece |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-life/doon-tunes/article28596325.ece |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]]. The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Doon-goes-musical/articleshow/6919938.cms |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations and partnerships==\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> \n\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=1440&start=1 |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/Is-the-old-school-tie-wearing-thin/articleshow/6800680.cms?referral=PM |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" as the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers, [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate (Seth novel)|The Golden Gate]]''|image2=Amitav Ghosh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Amitav Ghosh]] (Class of 1972), author of the ''[[Ibis trilogy]]'' and ''[[The Hungry Tide]]''}}\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> In politics, they include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Seven-Doon-alumni-in-15th-Lok-Sabha/article16568183.ece |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] and [[Rahul Gandhi]] were at school, and the [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]] [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930 |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=left|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].|image2=Ravi Matthai, father of IIMs.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Ravi J. Matthai|Ravi Matthai]] (Class of 1945), founder director of [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]]}}\n\nIn the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designs include Chicago's ''[[Cloud Gate]]'' and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].]]In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]]; [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/bonfire-of-vanities/267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 \n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/old-boys-want-doon-to-stay-as-it-is/cid/473019|title=Old boys want Doon to stay as it is|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October, 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-sundaymagazine/climb-every-mountain/article28515581.ece |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> \n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nThe annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys should leave The Doon School as members of an aristocracy, but it must be an aristocracy of service inspired by the ideals of unselfishness, not one of privilege, wealth or position\".<ref>''The Doon School Sixty Years On'', 1936, p.4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |page=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Lt.-Col.-Eric-Joseph-Simeon-dead/article14764255.ece |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms|title=Ramchandani: Old Boy and \u2018workaholic\u2019 headmaster who transformed Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon Cabinet\"<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /> or \"Dosco Mafia\",<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaster, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person, and the events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President of India [[Pratibha Patil]], King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan, and [[Kapil Sibal]], then minister of [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/dame-dilemma-for-doon-president-s-co-ed-suggestion-evokes-mixed-reaction/cid/473014 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, labelling the bullying scenes \"defamatory\", and obtained a court order to delay its release. The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-film-fallout/articleshow/6941433.cms|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Ex-students-film-celebrating-Doon-draws-schools-ire/articleshow/7159525.cms|title=Ex-student's film 'celebrating' Doon draws school's ire &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India]]n states.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Governance and organisation==\n\nThe school is owned by the [[non-profit]] entity Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which was registered by S.R. Das in 1928 with the aim of establishing public schools in India. Under the IPSS, the Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref> The current board comprises thirteen members and is chaired by [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], an alumnus. The president of [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]] has a seat on the board to represent the views and interests of the alumni.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> At the intramural level, the School Council, comprising the headmaster, heads of department, staff and student representatives from each house, is responsible for legislating and discussing school policies. Every house holds a vote to send four student representatives to the council. Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/class-up-at-doon/230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students at the start of the year by voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>   \n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Those who have a family history with a particular house are assigned to the same house. All houses have rooms, dormitories, kitchen, library, study rooms, and a Common Room for recreation.\n\n===Fees and financial aid===\nAs of April 2020, the annual school fees for Indian students was {{Indian Rupee}}10,25,000, and {{Indian Rupee}}12,81,000 for foreign nationals or [[non-resident Indians]]. Once admission is secured after passing the entrance examination and interview, a student can apply for around 25 scholarships or awards on offer. Some are reserved for boys proficient in sports or arts, and those from an [[Indian Armed Forces|armed forces]] background. The monetary value of financial aid ranges from fifty percent of the tuition fee to being fully funded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/admissions/scholarships/|title=Scholarship Programme Offered by The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> In the media, the school has been described as a \"grooming ground for India's wealthy kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> The last headmaster, Matthew Raggett, has stated that over 25% of Doon's students receive needs-based bursaries, and the school is working towards a completely [[need-blind admission|needs-blind admission]] policy.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. The buildings on campus include the Main Building, housing offices and classrooms, structures for sports facilities, science blocks, music school, library, arts and media centre, auditorium, amphitheatre, dining hall, wellness centre, recycling and waste-treatment plants, and masters' residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412|title=Premium schools &#124; Outlook Business|website=www.outlookbusiness.com}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]]. A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/doon-school-s-etp-may-be-trendsetter-111031400040_1.html |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:Main Building corridor at Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Ground-floor corridor of the school's Main Building, which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Chhota-Hazri-bell-tolls-for-desi-Etons/articleshow/764209.cms |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On Sundays, boys are free to pursue any activity or sport, or go into town for leisure.<ref name=\"Boarding at Doon\" /> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. The autumn term runs from August to the year-end final examinations in November, after which the boys are promoted to the new class in February.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> Each term has a \"test week\" and end-of-term examinations known as \"trials\". Boys meet their tutors every week to discuss any matter, and are able to visit teachers, most of whom live on campus, for further academic help. Subjects on offer include geography, economics, environmental studies, art and design, psychology, music, English, Hindi, Sanskrit, and [[STEM subjects]]. Doon's foreign language offerings include French, German and Spanish. There is a career's department that offers pupils guidance on career paths, college applications, and entrance exams like the [[SAT]]. In recent years, boys have increasingly chosen foreign universities over Indian colleges, sometimes due to the hyper-competitiveness of the [[Higher education in India|Indian higher education system]] that calls for extremely high school-leaving scores for admissions.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/education/it-is-an-elite-school-not-elitist/article23029951.ece|title=\u2018It is an elite school, not elitist\u2019|first=Jaideep Deo|last=Bhanj|date=11 March 2018|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref> Social work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/|title=F.C. Barcelona at Doon - July 2013|date=20 September 2013|website=Doon School}}</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://educationworld.in//EWIssue.aspx|title=India's best boys boarding school|website=EducationWorld.in}}</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m), during its first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the open-air theatre, Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/raga-meets-rhythm/article28369860.ece |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-life/doon-tunes/article28596325.ece |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]]. The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Doon-goes-musical/articleshow/6919938.cms |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations and partnerships==\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> \n\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=1440&start=1 |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/Is-the-old-school-tie-wearing-thin/articleshow/6800680.cms?referral=PM |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" as the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers, [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate (Seth novel)|The Golden Gate]]''|image2=Amitav Ghosh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Amitav Ghosh]] (Class of 1972), author of the ''[[Ibis trilogy]]'' and ''[[The Hungry Tide]]''}}\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> In politics, they include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/Seven-Doon-alumni-in-15th-Lok-Sabha/article16568183.ece |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]] and [[Rahul Gandhi]] were at school, and the [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]] [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930 |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> \n{{multiple image|align=right|direction=horizontal|header= |header_align=center\n |header_background =\n | footer =\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width =\n | image1=Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|width1=114|caption1=[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].|image2=Ravi Matthai, father of IIMs.jpg|width2=114|caption2=[[Ravi J. Matthai|Ravi Matthai]] (Class of 1945), founder director of [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]]}}\n\nIn the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> [[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designs include Chicago's ''[[Cloud Gate]]'' and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].]]In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]]; [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/bonfire-of-vanities/267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "CallMeByYourMane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people:align left", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School"}
{"title_page": "Tom Haddon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Tom Haddon\n|fullname       = Thomas Haddon\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|LK}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = 22\n|tries1         = 3\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 9\n|club2               = [[North Shore Albions]]\n|year2start          = 1925\n|year2end            = \n|appearances2        = 9 \n|tries2              = 4\n|goals2              = 0\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 12\n|teamA          = Auckland\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          =1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 2\n|triesB              = 0\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             = 0\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n'''Tom Haddon''' was a New Zealand rugby league player. He was Kiwi number 136 after playing two tests for New Zealand against Australia in 1919.\n\n==Early Life==\nIt is unclear where Thomas Haddon was born or raised. The first clear indication of him being in Auckland is with his debut for [[City Rovers]] in the opening game of the [[1918 Auckland Rugby League season]]. There are no records of him being born or marrying in [[New Zealand]]. At the start of 1920 he was thought to have moved to [[Australia]] to play rugby league but there are no records of him playing there after being given permission by the New Zealand Rugby League Council.\n\n==Playing career==\n===City Rovers, Auckland, and New Zealand===\nTom Haddon first appeared for [[City Rovers]] in 1918 in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition, playing for them against [[Grafton Athletic]] in a preliminary round to open the season <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Northern Union/Teams for Saturday/North Shore\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLIX, Issue 99\n| date = 1918-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19180426.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He scored a try in a Round 3 match against Grafton Athletic at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] where he \u201creceived a cross-kick and scored underneath the posts\u201d with City going on to win 11-10 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championship Matches/Newton V Ponsonby/Grafton V City\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16860\n| date = 1918-05-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180527.2.62.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. He scored against the same opponents in the second round in front of 5,000 spectators again at Victoria Park <ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Grafton\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16896\n| date = 1918-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180708.2.50\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nHe was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team in 1918 and played in the first proper inter provincial match that Auckland had played since [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]] (when they played Thames twice, and Lower Waikato once). During the war the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had decided to largely cease its representative program. Haddon\u2019s debut was against [[Canterbury rugby league team]] and it resulted in a comfortable 45-9 victory to Auckland with Haddon scoring twice. The match was played in front of 10,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Haddon was again playing for City and in a round two match against [[North Shore Albions]] on the Devonport Domain in front of 500 spectators <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championships Continue/City V North Shore\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17158\n| date = 1919-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190512.2.21.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>. On August 9, Haddon played for Auckland in a match against [[Hawke's Bay rugby league team|Hawke's Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] before a crowd of 9,000. Haddon scored 3 tries in a 38 to 13 victory <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. As this was to be his last game for Auckland it meant that he had scored 3 tries for his City team in 2 full seasons of club rugby league but managed to cross the line 5 times for Auckland in just 2 appearances.\n\nHaddon had been picked to tour Australia with the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team in June and July of 1919 but due to circumstances was unable to make the trip <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football/Northern Union\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 65\n| date = 1920-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200316.2.67.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He was however selected for the 3rd and 4th tests against the touring Australian team in August/September <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. On September 6, Tom Haddon became Kiwi number 136 when he played lock in front of 24,300 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]]. New Zealand were defeated 34 to 23 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Inter-Colonial League/The Kiwi and the Kangaroo\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 213\n| date = 1909-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190908.2.129\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. In the third test also played on the Domain, New Zealand was heavily beaten by 32 points to 2 with Haddon moving into the prop position <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The Last Test/Australia\u2019s Decisive Win\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume 219, Issue L\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190915.2.98\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nIn April, 1920 [[Auckland Rugby League]] gave its permission for Haddon to \u201cplay in any district outside Auckland\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The Auckland League\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17447\n| date = 1920-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200417.2.80.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then on May 10 the [[New Zealand Rugby League|New Zealand Rugby League Council]] granted him an open transfer to play in Australia as reported in the ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The New Zealand Council\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17467\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200511.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The ''[[Auckland Star]]'' suggesting that he \u201cwill probably play in Australia\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Affairs in Wellington/N.Z. Council Meets\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 112\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200511.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. It is however unclear as to where he went and if he played rugby league over the following years.\n\n===North Shore Albions===\nIn 1925 Haddon resumed playing rugby league in Auckland, this time however he was to represent the [[North Shore Albions]] who at this time were in fact named [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] after amalgamating with the Sunnyside League Football Club at the start of the 1920 season <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVII| issue=17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. The first mention of him in a Devonport uniform is in a match against his old [[City Rovers]] team at [[Carlaw Park]] where he scored a try <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Another Great Game/City Beat Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 133,\n| date = 1925-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250608.2.147\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The day was significant for other reasons as the teams stood in silence before the kick off out of respect for [[Bill Stormont]] (Kiwi #140) who had died two days earlier. In a July match Haddon scored a try in front of 9,000 spectators at Carlaw Park against [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Devonport won but not before Haddon was sent off along with Marist\u2019s New Zealand international [[Andrew O'Brien (rugby)|Jim O'Brien]] after a \u201crough-up\u201d between the two. Devonport won the match 19-11 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Devonport\u2019s Day Out/Marists v Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 145\n| date = 1925-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250622.2.108\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nAfter a July match between Ponsonby and Devonport it was said of Haddon \u201cit is surprising how youth sticks to some footballers. On Saturday the veteran \u2026 was easily Devonport\u2019s best forward. He showed a lot of pace and some of the form displayed several years ago when playing for [[City Rovers|City]]\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football Notes and Comments/The North Shore Players\n| page =6 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19069\n| date = 1925-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250714.2.9.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then against Athletic \u201cHaddon, following up fast secured, and beating several Athletic players, scored behind the posts with three men hanging on to him\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Club Competitions/Athletic v Devonport\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 169\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250720.2.137\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. He scored a second try later in the match after a \u201cpassing rush\u201d in which all the Devonport players took part. Haddon\u2019s final ever senior league match was in a Roope Rooster semi final loss to his old City Rovers team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/City Defeat Devonport\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926, 27, 28, and again in 1934 Haddon played in several veteran player exhibition matches. On October 30, 1926 Haddon made an appearance in an end of season game played between well known league veterans at Carlaw Park. Haddon was representing early New Zealand rugby league legends [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = End of Season Games/Veteran Players in Action\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19473\n| date = 1926-11-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19261101.2.138\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The match finished 10-10 and featured the likes of [[Eric Bennett (New Zealand)|Eric Bennett]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], and [[Thomas McClymont]]. In September, 1927 he was chosen in a Devonport United veteran team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby League/Devonport United\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 207\n| date = 1927-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19270902.2.138.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. Then again in October he played for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against \u201cShaver\u201d Hargreaves team. The match featured [[Ernie Asher]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|Billy Wynyard]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], and [[Bert Laing]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Relief of Unemployed\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 248\n| date = 1927-10-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19271020.2.150\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He played in another match in 1928 between City and Ponsonby and then again in 1934 once again for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, 24 September\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280924.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Charity Day\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXV, Issue 244\n| date = 1934-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19341015.2.153\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n===Mt Albert Selector===\nIn 1935 and 36 Tom Haddon was elected as a selector for the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert United Football Club]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Mt Albert United Club\n| page = 16\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 53\n| date = 1936-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360303.2.193\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/The Coming Season\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 87\n| date = 1936-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360413.2.149\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddon, Tom}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Tom Haddon\n|fullname       = Thomas Haddon\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|LK}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = 22\n|tries1         = 3\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 9\n|club2               = [[North Shore Albions]]\n|year2start          = 1925\n|year2end            = \n|appearances2        = 9 \n|tries2              = 4\n|goals2              = 0\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 12\n|teamA          = Auckland\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          =1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 2\n|triesB              = 0\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             = 0\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n'''Tom Haddon''' was a New Zealand rugby league player. He was Kiwi number 136 after playing two tests for New Zealand against Australia in 1919.\n\n==Early Life==\nIt is unclear where Thomas Haddon was born or raised. The first clear indication of him being in Auckland is with his debut for [[City Rovers]] in the opening game of the [[1918 Auckland Rugby League season]]. There are no records of him being born or marrying in [[New Zealand]]. At the start of 1920 he was thought to have moved to [[Australia]] to play rugby league but there are no records of him playing there after being given permission by the New Zealand Rugby League Council.\n\n==Playing career==\n===City Rovers, Auckland, and New Zealand===\nTom Haddon first appeared for [[City Rovers]] in 1918 in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition, playing for them against [[Grafton Athletic]] in a preliminary round to open the season <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Northern Union/Teams for Saturday/North Shore\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLIX, Issue 99\n| date = 1918-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19180426.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He scored a try in a Round 3 match against Grafton Athletic at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] where he \u201creceived a cross-kick and scored underneath the posts\u201d with City going on to win 11-10 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championship Matches/Newton V Ponsonby/Grafton V City\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16860\n| date = 1918-05-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180527.2.62.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. He scored against the same opponents in the second round in front of 5,000 spectators again at Victoria Park <ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Grafton\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16896\n| date = 1918-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180708.2.50\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nHe was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team in 1918 and played in the first proper inter provincial match that Auckland had played since [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]] (when they played Thames twice, and Lower Waikato once). During the war the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had decided to largely cease its representative program. Haddon\u2019s debut was against [[Canterbury rugby league team]] and it resulted in a comfortable 45-9 victory to Auckland with Haddon scoring twice. The match was played in front of 10,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Haddon was again playing for City and in a round two match against [[North Shore Albions]] on the Devonport Domain in front of 500 spectators <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championships Continue/City V North Shore\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17158\n| date = 1919-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190512.2.21.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>. On August 9, Haddon played for Auckland in a match against [[Hawke's Bay rugby league team|Hawke's Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] before a crowd of 9,000. Haddon scored 3 tries in a 38 to 13 victory <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. As this was to be his last game for Auckland it meant that he had scored 3 tries for his City team in 2 full seasons of club rugby league but managed to cross the line 5 times for Auckland in just 2 appearances.\n\nHaddon had been picked to tour Australia with the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team in June and July of 1919 but due to circumstances was unable to make the trip <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football/Northern Union\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 65\n| date = 1920-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200316.2.67.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He was however selected for the 3rd and 4th tests against the touring Australian team in August/September <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. On September 6, Tom Haddon became Kiwi number 136 when he played lock in front of 24,300 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]]. New Zealand were defeated 34 to 23 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Inter-Colonial League/The Kiwi and the Kangaroo\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 213\n| date = 1909-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190908.2.129\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. In the third test also played on the Domain, New Zealand was heavily beaten by 32 points to 2 with Haddon moving into the prop position <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The Last Test/Australia\u2019s Decisive Win\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume 219, Issue L\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190915.2.98\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nIn April, 1920 [[Auckland Rugby League]] gave its permission for Haddon to \u201cplay in any district outside Auckland\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The Auckland League\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17447\n| date = 1920-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200417.2.80.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then on May 10 the [[New Zealand Rugby League|New Zealand Rugby League Council]] granted him an open transfer to play in Australia as reported in the ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The New Zealand Council\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17467\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200511.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The ''[[Auckland Star]]'' suggesting that he \u201cwill probably play in Australia\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Affairs in Wellington/N.Z. Council Meets\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 112\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200511.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. It is however unclear as to where he went and if he played rugby league over the following years.\n\n===North Shore Albions===\nIn 1925 Haddon resumed playing rugby league in Auckland, this time however he was to represent the [[North Shore Albions]] who at this time were in fact named [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] after amalgamating with the Sunnyside League Football Club at the start of the 1920 season <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVII| issue=17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. The first mention of him in a Devonport uniform is in a match against his old [[City Rovers]] team at [[Carlaw Park]] where he scored a try <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Another Great Game/City Beat Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 133,\n| date = 1925-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250608.2.147\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The day was significant for other reasons as the teams stood in silence before the kick off out of respect for [[Bill Stormont]] (Kiwi #140) who had died two days earlier. In a July match Haddon scored a try in front of 9,000 spectators at Carlaw Park against [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Devonport won but not before Haddon was sent off along with Marist\u2019s New Zealand international [[Andrew O'Brien (rugby)|Jim O'Brien]] after a \u201crough-up\u201d between the two. Devonport won the match 19-11 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Devonport\u2019s Day Out/Marists v Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 145\n| date = 1925-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250622.2.108\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nAfter a July match between Ponsonby and Devonport it was said of Haddon \u201cit is surprising how youth sticks to some footballers. On Saturday the veteran \u2026 was easily Devonport\u2019s best forward. He showed a lot of pace and some of the form displayed several years ago when playing for [[City Rovers|City]]\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football Notes and Comments/The North Shore Players\n| page =6 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19069\n| date = 1925-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250714.2.9.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then against Athletic \u201cHaddon, following up fast secured, and beating several Athletic players, scored behind the posts with three men hanging on to him\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Club Competitions/Athletic v Devonport\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 169\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250720.2.137\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. He scored a second try later in the match after a \u201cpassing rush\u201d in which all the Devonport players took part. Haddon\u2019s final ever senior league match was in a Roope Rooster semi final loss to his old City Rovers team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/City Defeat Devonport\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926, 27, 28, and again in 1934 Haddon played in several veteran player exhibition matches. On October 30, 1926 Haddon made an appearance in an end of season game played between well known league veterans at Carlaw Park. Haddon was representing early New Zealand rugby league legends [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = End of Season Games/Veteran Players in Action\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19473\n| date = 1926-11-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19261101.2.138\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The match finished 10-10 and featured the likes of [[Eric Bennett (New Zealand)|Eric Bennett]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], and [[Thomas McClymont]]. In September, 1927 he was chosen in a Devonport United veteran team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby League/Devonport United\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 207\n| date = 1927-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19270902.2.138.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. Then again in October he played for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against \u201cShaver\u201d Hargreaves team. The match featured [[Ernie Asher]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|Billy Wynyard]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], and [[Bert Laing]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Relief of Unemployed\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 248\n| date = 1927-10-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19271020.2.150\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He played in another match in 1928 between City and Ponsonby and then again in 1934 once again for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, 24 September\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280924.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Charity Day\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXV, Issue 244\n| date = 1934-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19341015.2.153\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n===Mt Albert Selector===\nIn 1935 and 36 Tom Haddon was elected as a selector for the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Mt Albert United Club\n| page = 16\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 53\n| date = 1936-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360303.2.193\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/The Coming Season\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 87\n| date = 1936-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360413.2.149\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddon, Tom}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMt Albert Selector", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Haddon"}
{"title_page": "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (British game show)", "text_new": "{{About|the original UK version|the international franchise|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = {{nowrap|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?}}\n| image                    = WWTBAM20thTitle.png\n| caption                  = Titlecard for the revived series of the show (20th anniversary version)\n| genre                    = [[Quiz show]]\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* David Briggs\n* [[Steven Knight|Steve Knight]]\n* Mike Whitehill\n}}\n| presenter                = <!--No years or seasons as per template-->{{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris Tarrant]] <small>(1998\u20132014)</small> \n* [[Jeremy Clarkson]] <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Keith Strachan]] <small>(1998\u20132007{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}, 2018\u2013present)</small> \n* [[Matthew Strachan]] <small>(1998\u20132007{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}, 2018\u2013present)</small> \n* Ramon Covalo <small>(2007\u201314) </small>\n</small>\n}}\n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language                 = [[English language|English]]\n| num_series               = 34\n| num_episodes             = 625 <!--as of Sunday 5 Jan 2020-->\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fountain Studios]] <small>(1998\u20131999)</small>\n* [[Elstree Studios]] <small>(1999\u20132014)</small>\n* [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| runtime                  = 30\u201380 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Celador]] <small>(1998\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Carlton Television|Carlton]] <small>(1998)</small>\n* [[2waytraffic]] <small>(2007\u201310)</small>\n* [[Sony Pictures Television|Victory Television]] <small>(2011\u201314)</small>\n* [[Stellify Media]] <small>(2018\u2013)</small>\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Celador International]]/[[2waytraffic|2waytraffic International]] (1998\u20132009)<br>[[Sony Pictures Television International|Sony Pictures Television International Distribution]] (2009\u2013present)\n| producer                 = Fiona Clark (as of 2018 revival)\n| network                  = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| picture_format           = [[4:3]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small><br>[[16:9]] <small>(1999\u2013)</small>\n| first_aired              = '''Original series:'''<br>{{Start date|1998|9|4|df=y}}&nbsp;\u2013 {{end date|2014|2|11|df=y}}<br>'''Revived series:'''<br> {{Start date|2018|5|5|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.millionaire-show.com/\n}}\n\n'''''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''''' is a British television quiz show, created and produced by David Briggs, and made for the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] network. On air since September 1998 and devised by Briggs, the show's format sees contestants taking on multiple-choice questions based upon general knowledge, winning a cash prize for each question they answer correctly, with the amount offered increasing as they take on more difficult questions. To assist each contestant who takes part, they are given lifelines to use, may walk away with the money they already have won if they wish not to risk answering a question, and are provided with a safety net that gives them a guaranteed cash prize if they give an incorrect answer, provided they reach a specific milestone in the quiz.\n\nThe original series aired for 30 series and aired a total of 592 episodes, from 4 September 1998 to 11 February 2014, and was presented by [[Chris Tarrant]]. Over the course of its initial run, the show had five contestants achieve the show\u2019s ultimate aim and walk away with the cash prize of \u00a31&nbsp;million. The original format of the programme was tweaked in later years; this included changing the number of questions from fifteen to twelve, altering the payout structure and later incorporating a time limit which included an attainable fourth lifeline. There were several controversies during its run, including an attempt by a contestant to [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|defraud the show of its top prize]].\n\nFour years after the original series ended, ITV announced that the series would be revived, this time produced by [[Stellify Media]], to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the programme. The revival was based closely on the show\u2019s original format. It was hosted by [[Jeremy Clarkson]] and filmed at [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10 studios]]. The success of the revival series has ensured that subsequent series of the show have been commissioned, and in January 2019 the show reached the milestone of 600 episodes since first appearing on air.\n\nThe game show became one of the most significant shows in British popular culture, ranking 23rd in a list of the [[BFI TV 100|100 Greatest British Television Programmes]] compiled in 2000 by the [[British Film Institute]]. It was the highest quiz programme to appear on the list. Its success led to versions in [[International versions of Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|many other countries]] under an [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|international franchise of the same name]], all of which follow the same general format, though with some versions including unique differences in gameplay and lifelines provided.\n\n==History==\n{{Multiple image\n| direction = horizontal\n| width =\n| align = right\n| header = UK presenters of ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''\n| image1 = Chris Tarrant Phooto.jpg\n| image2 = Jeremy Clarkson.jpg\n| width1 = 130\n| width2 = 135\n| caption1 = [[Chris Tarrant]] (1998\u20132014)\n| caption2 = [[Jeremy Clarkson]] (2018\u2013present)\n| alt1 = Tarrant\n| alt2 = Clarkson\n}}\n\n===Creation===\nThe creation of the game show was led by David Briggs, assisted by Mike Whitehill and Steven Knight, who had helped him before with creating a number of promotional games for Chris Tarrant's [[Capital Breakfast|morning show]] on [[95.8 Capital FM|Capital FM]] radio. The basic premise for the show was a twist on the conventional game-show genre of the time, with a focus towards the setup used in radio quizzes, in that the programme would have one contestant taking on the game and answering questions, but with the ability to pull out at any time, to have certain points in the quiz where once passed, they could have a set prize given to them if they should give a wrong answer, and be provided with special forms of assistance during their game. During the design phase, the show was given the [[working title]] of \"Cash Mountain\", before Briggs decided upon using the name of the [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (song)|song]] written by [[Cole Porter]] for the 1956 film ''[[High Society (1956 film)|High Society]]'', as the show's finalised title.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> After presenting their idea to [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], the broadcaster gave the green-light for production to begin on a series.\n\nThe set designed for ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was conceived by British [[production designer]] [[Andy Walmsley]], who focused the design towards making contestants feel uncomfortable, creating an atmosphere of tension similar to [[Thriller film|movie thriller]].<ref name=\"Walmsley\">{{Cite web|title=Millionaire|url=http://www.andywalmsley.com/millionaire.php|publisher=Andy Walmsley, Production Designer|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> The design was in stark contrast to the design of sets made for more typical game shows, which are designed to make contestants feel more at ease.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> Walmsley's design feature a central stage made primarily with [[Plexiglas]], with a huge dish underneath covered in mirror paper,<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/><ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> onto which two slightly-modified, {{convert|3|foot|m}}-high Pietranera Arco All chairs were chosen for use by both the contestant and the host, each having an [[LG Electronics|LG]] computer monitor directly facing each that would be used to display questions and other pertinent information. The rest of the set featured seating spaced out around the main stage in a circle, with breaks in them to allow movement of people on and off the set. The lighting rig used for the set was designed so as to allow only the lights to switch from illuminating the entire set, to focusing on the host and contestant on the main stage when a game was underway, but to include special lighting effects when the contestant reached higher cash prize amounts. His overall conception would eventually prove to be a success, becoming one of the most reproduced scenic designs in television history.<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/>\n\nThe music provided for the show was composed by father-and-son duo [[Keith Strachan|Keith]] and [[Matthew Strachan]]. The Strachans' composition for the game show helped with Briggs' tense game design, by providing the necessary drama and tension. Unlike other game show musical scores, the music provided for ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was designed to be played throughout the entire episode of the show. The Strachans main theme for the game show was inspired from the \"Mars\" movement of [[Gustav Holst]]'s ''[[The Planets]]''. For the main game of the show, the pair designed the music to feature three variations, with the second and third compositions focused on emphasising the increased tension of the game \u2013 as a contestant made progress to higher cash amounts, the pitch of the music was increased by a semitone for each subsequent question.<ref name=\"Million Dollar Notes\">{{cite news|title=Million Pound Notes: Keith Strachan|last=Smurthwaite|first=Nick|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=21 March 2005|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612081217/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archivedate=12 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> On [[Game Show Network]]'s ''Gameshow Hall of Fame'' special, the narrator described the Strachan tracks as \"mimicking the sound of a beating heart\", and stated that as the contestant works their way up the money ladder, the music is \"perfectly in tune with their ever-increasing pulse\".<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\">{{Cite episode|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|series=Gameshow Hall of Fame|publisher=GSN|date=21 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Original series===\nWith the show created, ITV assigned [[Chris Tarrant]] as its host, and set its premiere to 4 September 1998. The programme was assigned a timeslot of one hour, to provide room for three commercial breaks, with episodes produced by UK production company [[Celador]]. Originally, the show was broadcast on successive evenings for around ten days, before the network modified its broadcast schedule in autumn 2000<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/29/broadcasting3|title=Millionaire ratings slide|first=Jason|last=Deans|date=29 November 2001|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> to air it within a primetime slot on Saturday evenings, with occasional broadcasts on Tuesday evenings. ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' proved a ratings hit, pulling in average viewing figures of up to 19 million during its broadcast in 1999 (all-time high was on 7 March 1999, 19.2 million viewers),<ref name=\"auto\"/> though such figures often occurred when the programme was allocated to a half-hour timeslot. By September 2000 viewing figures had dropped to 11.1 million viewers,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and by 2003 to an average of around 8&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Millionaire: A TV phenomenon|work=BBC News|date=3 March 2003|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2783505.stm|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Audiences continued to drop<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/jan/26/overnights|title=TV ratings: January 23\u201324|first=Claire|last=Cozens|date=26 January 2004|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> and from 2005 to 2011 the show usually attracted between 3 and 4 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/03/ITV.overnights|title=TV ratings: April 30|first=Julia|last=Day|date=3 May 2005|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jan/23/tvratings.television|title=TV ratings \u2013 January 22: Ladettes fail to attract viewers to ITV|first=Leigh|last=Holmwood|date=23 January 2008|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/01/the-bill-finale-tv-ratings|title=The Bill finale wins 4.4m viewers &#124; TV ratings \u2013 31 August|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=1 September 2010|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> At one point in September 1999, an episode had 60% of the TV share and caused the [[BBC]] an historic low in ratings.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Over the course of his time presenting the game show, Tarrant developed a number of notable catchphrases, including \"Is that your final answer?\", \"But we don't want to give you that\" and \"Audience, all on your keypads please. All Vote Now!\" with the latter often used to emphasise his wish to see contestants continue on and win more money and audience allowed to vote the answers in the lifeline used.\n\nSince its launch, several individuals made claims over the origins of the format or elements of it, with each accusing Celador of breaching their copyrights. In three cases, the matters could not be proven by the claimants \u2013 in 2002, Mike Bull, a [[Southampton]]-based journalist, was given an out-of-court settlement when he claimed the authorship of lifelines was his work, though with a confidentiality clause attached; in 2003, Sydney resident John J. Leonard made claims in that the show's format was based on one he had made of a similar nature, but without the concept of lifelines;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xavierax.com/ebook.pdf |title=Millionaire 2nd Edition.qxd |format=PDF |last=Leonard |first=John J. |year=2005 |accessdate=2 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801163453/http://www.xavierax.com/ebook.pdf |archive-date=1 August 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The show that should have made me a million|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/03/29/1048653901387.html|first=Daniel |last=Dasey|newspaper=The Sydney Sun-Herald|date=30 March 2003}}</ref> in 2004, Alan Melville was given an out-of-court settlement after he claimed that the opening phrase \"Who wants to be a millionaire?\" had been taken from a document he sent to [[Granada Television]], concerning his idea for a game show based on the lottery.\n\nOne of most significant claims Celador received against them was from John Bachini. In 2002, he started legal proceedings against the production company, ITV, and five individuals who had claimed they had created ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', stating that the idea from the show was taken from several elements he had created \u2013 a board game format he conceived in 1981; a two-page TV format, known as ''Millionaire'', made in 1987; and the telephone mechanics for a TV concept he created in 1989, ''BT Lottery''. In his claim, Bachini stated that he submitted documents for his TV concepts to Paul Smith, from a sister company of Celador's, in March 1995 and again in January 1996, and to [[Claudia Rosencrantz]] of ITV, also in January 1996, accusing both of using roughly 90% of the format for ''Millionaire'' in the pilot for the game show, including the use of twenty questions, lifelines and safety nets, although the lifelines were conceived under different names \u2013 Bachini claimed that he never coined the phrase \"phone-a-friend\" that Briggs designed in his format. In response to this claim, Celador made a counter-claim that the franchise originated from the basic format idea conceived by Briggs. The defendants in the claim took Bachini to a summary hearing but lost their right to have his claim dismissed. Although Bachini won the right to go to trial, he was unable to after the hearing due to serious illness. Celador eventually settled the matter with him out-of-court.<ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/sundaymercury/news/tm_objectid=15908484&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=who-wants-to-sue-a-millionaire-name_page.html Birmingham Sunday Mercury], 28 August 2005</ref>\n\nIn March 2006, Celador began procedures to sell the format of the show and all UK episodes, as part of their first step towards the sale of their formats divisions. The purchase of both assets was made by Dutch company [[2waytraffic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toynews-online.biz/news/read/new-owners-take-on-celador-international-and-millionaire-brand/039482|title=New owners take on Celador International and Millionaire brand|publisher=toynews-online.biz|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|date=1 December 2006|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref> which were then passed on to [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] in 2008 when it acquired 2waytraffic.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2008/more/news/sony-pictures-acquires-2waytraffic-1117986861/|title=Sony Pictures acquires 2waytraffic|magazine=Variety|last=Levine|first=Stuart|date=4 June 2008|accessdate=19 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308125215/http://variety.com/2008/scene/news/sony-pictures-acquires-2waytraffic-1117986861/|archivedate=8 March 2014}}</ref> As the original series progressed, variations of the format were created, and screened as special episodes, including celebrity editions, games featuring couples as contestants, and episodes themed around special events such as Mother's Day.\n\nThe Christmas Eve celebrity special from December 2010 drew its biggest audience since 2006. To capitalise on this, and breathe new life into the now 12-year-old show,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/12/itv-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire|title=ITV looks to revive Millionaire's sparkle|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=12 January 2011|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> from April 2011 only celebrity contestants appeared on the show, in special live editions that coincided with holidays, events and other notable moments, such as the end of a [[school term]]. However, in 2012, three special episodes, entitled \"The People Play\", were broadcast for three consecutive nights between 9 and 11 July. They featured standard contestants, with viewers at home allowed to play along.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millionaire.itv.com/be-a-contestant/ |title=This summer, Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? will once again be going live, but this time with the Great British public in the hotseat! |publisher=ITV |accessdate=7 November 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530075910/http://millionaire.itv.com/be-a-contestant/|archivedate=30 May 2012}}</ref> The special was used three more times in 2013, once on 7 May, and twice more on 21 May, before the special's format was discontinued.\n\nOn 22 October 2013, Tarrant announced that, after fifteen years of hosting the programme, he would be leaving ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', which consequently led ITV to axe the programme once his contract was finished; no more specials would be filmed after this announcement, leaving only those made before it to be aired as the final episodes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/who-wants-millionaire-axed-host-2479545 |title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire axed as host Chris Tarrant decided 'it was time to take a break' |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.u.tv/entertainment/Millionaire-axed-as-Tarrant-quits/73946d68-1f14-4ad2-9d20-912ca13e275c |title=Millionaire axed as Tarrant quits |website=[[UTV Media|u.tv]] |accessdate=22 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022152601/http://www.u.tv/entertainment/Millionaire-axed-as-Tarrant-quits/73946d68-1f14-4ad2-9d20-912ca13e275c |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> After a few more celebrity editions of the game show, Tarrant hosted his final episode, a [[clip show]] entitled \"Chris' Final Answer\", which aired on 11 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-chriss-final-answer-tv-review-tarrant-isnt-quite-on-the-money-with-9122226.html|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Chris's Final Answer \u2013 TV review: 'Tarrant isn't quite on the money'|date=12 February 2014|first=Ellen |last=Jones|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Revival===\nIn 2018, ITV revived the show for a new series, as part of its 20th anniversary commemorations of the programme. On 23 February, the broadcast put out a casting call for contestants who would appear on the game show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/beontv/shows/whowantstobeamillionaire|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?|date=23 February 2018|publisher=itv.com|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> On 9 March, [[Jeremy Clarkson]] was confirmed as the new host of the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43342726|title=Jeremy Clarkson replaces Chris Tarrant on Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?|work=BBC News|date=9 March 2018}}</ref> On 13 April, the trailer for the revival premiered on ITV and confirmed that the show would return in May for a week-long run.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a854690/jeremy-clarkson-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-itv-revival-trailer/|title=ITV releases trailer for Jeremy Clarkson's Who Wants to Be a Millionaire revival|last=Lee|first=Ben|date=13 April 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Shows aired from 5 May to 11 May and were filmed in Studio HQ2 at [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] in [[Greater Manchester]]. The first episode drew an average of 5.06 million viewers, a 29.7% TV share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/956427/Who-Wants-To-Be-A-Millionaire-Jeremy-Clarkson-Chris-Tarrant-Ratings-Viewers-Comparison-ITV|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire: Jeremy Clarkson and Chris Tarrant\u2019s ratings war REVEALED|first=Rory|last=O'Connor|date=7 May 2018|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nITV renewed the show for another series, with Clarkson returning as host. It aired for 6 episodes from 1 to 6 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? returns to ITV in 2019 |url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/who-wants-be-millionaire-returns-itv-2019 |website=www.ITV.com |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> The second half of the second series began on 4 March 2019 with 5 episodes. The third series began on 24 August 2019 with 11 episodes with the episodes airing like the old format once weekly.\n\nITV then renewed a fourth series for a celebrity edition of the show, with Clarkson returning as host and showing 4 episodes airing on 25 December 2019, (a Christmas Special), 4 January 2020, 5 January and 12 April. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week52/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 1|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep2week2/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 2|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep3week2/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 3|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week16/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 1|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Top prize winners===\nOver the course of the programme's broadcast history, it has had five (six if [[Charles Ingram]] was counted) winners who received its top prize of \u00a31 million. They are:\n\n* [[Judith Keppel]],<ref>Charles Mosley (ed.), ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage'' (London: Burke's Peerage, 1999)</ref> a former garden designer. On 20 November 2000, she became the first contestant to win the top prize. Following her success, Keppel later went onto become part of team of quiz experts for the BBC game show, ''[[Eggheads (TV series)|Eggheads]]''.\n* [[David Edwards (Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? contestant)|David Edwards]], a former physics teacher of [[Cheadle High School]] and [[Denstone College]] in [[Staffordshire]]. On 21 April 2001, he became the second contestant to win the top prize. Following his success, Edwards went on to compete in both series of ''[[Are You an Egghead?]]'', in 2008 and 2009 respectively, but failed to win either series and secure a place as a panellist on ''Eggheads''.\n*Charles Ingram, a former [[British army]] [[major]] in [[Shardlow]], [[Derbyshire]]. On 10 September 2001, he became the third person to win the top prize. Due to his actions on the show and being suspended in his trial, he didn't actually became the third person to win the top prize.\n* Robert Brydges,<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1566029.stm|title=Fourth Millionaire 'is millionaire'|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 August 2014|date=29 September 2001}}</ref> an [[Oxford]]-educated banker from [[Holland Park]], [[London]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1358013/Millionaire-quiz-show-aims-to-broaden-appeal.html|title='Millionaire' quiz show aims to broaden appeal|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=1 August 2013|location=London}}</ref> On 29 September 2001, he became the third (fourth if Charles was counted) person to win the show's top prize.<!-- Regardless of some Ref titles say, he was the third million pound winner, .--><ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a3888/fourth-contestant-wins-millionaire.html|title=Fourth contestant wins 'Millionaire'|website=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"thefreelibrary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/THANKS+A+MILLION..+WE'RE+BOTH+WINNERS%3b+EXCLUSIVE%3a+Couple+each+scoop...-a078293637|title=THANKS A MILLION.. WE'RE BOTH WINNERS; EXCLUSIVE: Couple each scoop TV prize.|publisher=[[Free Online Library]]|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2003/apr/19/weekend7.weekend6|title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part one|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Pat Gibson]], a multiple world champion Irish quiz player. On 24 April 2004, he became the fourth (fifth if Charles was counted) person to win the top prize.\n* [[Ingram Wilcox]], a British [[quiz]] enthusiast. On 23 September 2006, he became the fifth (sixth if Charles was counted) person to win the top prize.\n\n==Format==\n\n===Auditioning===\n\nDuring the original run, members of the public who wished to apply for the game show were provided with four options to choose from \u2013 calling/texting a premium-rate number; submitting an application via the show's ITV website, using a system of \u00a31 \u2018credits\u2019, or taking part in a casting audition, which were held at various locations around the UK. Once an application was made, production staff selected an episode's contestants through a combination of random selection, and a potential contestant's ability to answer a set of test questions based on general knowledge.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===Game rules=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right\"\t\n|-\t\n!colspan=4 style=\"background: #58B9E4\"| Payout structure\t\n|-\t\n!rowspan=2| Question<br>number\t\n!colspan=3| Question value\t\n|-\t\n! 1998\u20132007; 2018\u2013present\t\n! 2007\u20132014\t\n|-\t\n| 1\t\n| \u00a3100\t\n| \u00a3500\t\t\n|-\t\n| 2\t\n| \u00a3200\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a31,000'''\t\n|-\t\n| 3\t\n| \u00a3300\t\n| \u00a32,000\t\n|-\t\n| 4\t\n| \u00a3500\t\n| \u00a35,000\t\n|-\t\n| 5\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a31,000'''\t\n| \u00a310,000\t\n|-\t\n| 6\t\n| \u00a32,000\t\n| \u00a320,000\t\n|-\t\n| 7\t\n| \u00a34,000\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a350,000'''\t\n|-\t\n| 8\t\n| \u00a38,000\t\n| \u00a375,000\t\n|-\t\n| 9\t\n| \u00a316,000\t\n| \u00a3150,000\t\n|-\t\n| 10\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a332,000'''\t\n| \u00a3250,000\t\n|-\t\n| 11\t\n| \u00a364,000\t\n| \u00a3500,000\t\n|-\t\n| 12\t\n| \u00a3125,000\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''''\u00a31,000,000'''''\t\n|-\t\n| 13\t\n| \u00a3250,000\t\n| rowspan=3 {{N/A}}\t\n|-\t\n| 14\t\n| \u00a3500,000\n|-\t\n| 15\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''''\u00a31,000,000'''''\t\n|-\n\t\n|}\n\nOnce contestants auditioned for a part on the programme and filming took place, they undertook a preliminary round entitled \"Fastest Finger First\". Initially, the round required contestants to provide the correct answer to a question, but from series 2 onwards, they were tasked with putting four answers in the correct order stated within the question (i.e. earliest to latest). The contestant who answered the question correctly, and in the fastest time, won the opportunity to play the main game. In the event that no one answered the question correctly, a new question was asked, while if two or more contestants gave the correct answer in the same time, there was a tiebreaker question to determine who proceeded to the main game. The round was primarily used to determine the next contestant for the main game, and was more often than not used more than once in an episode.\n\nUpon completion of the preliminary round, the contestant began the main game, tackling a series of increasingly difficult questions, which offered progressively higher sums of money, up to the top prize of \u00a31,000,000. The stacks of 15 questions were randomly chosen from a list of pre generated questions based on general knowledge. For each question there were four options to choose from, labelled \u2018A\u2019, \u2018B\u2019, \u2018C\u2019 and \u2018D\u2019. During the game, contestants were allowed to use a set of 3 lifelines to help them with a question at any time, and two monetary safety nets were provided: if a contestant got a question wrong, but had reached a designated cash value during their game, they left with that amount as their prize. If a contestant was unsure about a question they were facing, they were allowed to leave the game at that point with the cash amount they had already won. While the initial questions were typically generally easy, the subsequent ones after it required the contestant to confirm that their answer/decision is final, at which point it became locked in and could not be reversed. As a rule, host Tarrant was not shown the correct answer on his monitor until a contestant had given their final answer. If an episode had reached the end of its allotted time, an audio cue was triggered to highlight this; contestants who were still playing the main game were left to wait until filming for the next episode began before they could continue, though this was not the case for special editions of the show, such as celebrity episodes.\n\nOver the course of the show's history on British television, the format of the programme has been altered in a number of aspects, mainly towards the setup of questions and the payout structure used in the game show, along with minor tweaks and changes in other aspects:\n* Between September 1998 and July 2007, contestants had to answer 15 questions, with two safety nets placed at \u00a31,000 and \u00a332,000, and they were allowed three standard lifelines.\n* Between August 2007 and February 2014, the number of questions was reduced to 12, with most cash values adjusted. This alteration led to the second safety net being assigned to \u00a350,000.\n* From the start of the 27th series in August 2010, the format was changed to include a clock format, similar to the 2008\u201310 US version, but with some differences. The time limit was 15 seconds for the first two questions, and 30 seconds for the next five questions, but the last five questions had no time limit. The clock would start ticking down as soon as the answers appeared on screen, and the contestant would have to give his/her final answer within the time limit. If they ran out of time it was treated as an incorrect answer. The clock would briefly pause, however, if any lifeline was used. It also added a new, fourth lifeline, Switch, which would be made available after passing question seven. The first episode of this series also saw the discontinuation of 'Fastest Finger First' for the first time since the inception of the show, so the contestants were then pre-selected by the production staff.\n* For the revival in 2018 and subsequent series of the show, the show returned to the 1998\u20132007 format, including the original payout structure and fastest finger process, with minor differences. A new lifeline, \u2018Ask The Host\u2019, was introduced and the placement of the second safety net could be set by the contestant. Upon reaching \u00a31,000, the contestant would be asked before each subsequent question if they would like to set the safety net to the cash value, with it offered up to question 14, \u00a3500,000. The number of contestants for 'Fastest Finger First' were also reduced from ten to six.\n* At the end of the allotted time of each standard episode, a loud sound (one long brass note) indicates the end of the show. The host refers to this noise as the \u2018klaxon\u2019. During the live specials whilst Tarrant was host, the contestant's game would end and any question in play would be null and void unless they gave a final answer before the klaxon sounded. The contestant\u2019s game then carries on at the start of the next episode.\n\n===Lifelines===\nDuring a contestant's game, they may make use of a set of lifelines to assist them on a question. Each lifeline may only be used once. Throughout the course of the show's history, these lifelines involve the following:\n* '''50:50''': (1998\u2013present): Two random incorrect answers are eliminated by the computer, leaving the correct answer and the one remaining incorrect answer, thus granting the contestant a 50/50 chance of answering the question correctly.\n* '''Phone a Friend''': (1998\u2013present): The contestant calls one of their friends, and has 30 seconds to read the question and answers to them. The friend uses the leftover time to offer an answer. Since 2011, a member of the production team accompanies the friend to prevent cheating, such as using the Internet or reading books, and is verified by the presenter before the contestant can confer.\n* '''Ask the Audience''': (1998\u2013present): Audience members use keypads to vote on what they believe to be the correct answer to the question they\u2019ve been asked. The percentage of each option selected by the audience is displayed to the contestant and audience after this vote.\n* '''Switch/Flip''' (2002\u201303, 2010\u201314): The computer replaces one question with another of the same monetary value. Any lifelines already used on the original question are not reinstated. In its original run, Switch was originally called \"Flip\" and could only be used if the contestant traded an unused lifeline for it, using it up to three times. From 2010 to 2014, this lifeline was separated and became available after the contestant answered seven questions correctly.\n* '''Ask the Host''' (2018\u2013present): The presenter offers advice or an answer to the question they are asked. The host usually discloses that he has no contact with outside sources, and there is no time limit as to how long he can offer help. The question's answer is not revealed to the host when this lifeline is used; instead, the computer reveals the answer to the host and contestant at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/who-wants-be-millionaire-returns-itv-saturday-brand-new-twists|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? returns to ITV this Saturday with brand new twists|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n===Main series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Series\n!Start date\n!End date\n!Episodes\n!Presenter\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|4 September 1998\n|25 December 1998\n|10\n| rowspan=\"30\" |[[Chris Tarrant]]\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|1 January 1999\n|13 January 1999\n|13\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|5 March 1999\n|16 March 1999\n|12\n|-\n|'''4'''\n|3 September 1999\n|14 September 1999\n|13\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|5 November 1999\n|25 December 1999\n|18\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|16 January 2000\n|22 January 2000\n|7\n|-\n|'''7'''\n|26 March 2000\n|1 May 2000\n|13\n|-\n|'''8'''\n|7 September 2000\n|6 January 2001\n|55\n|-\n|'''9'''\n|8 January 2001\n|26 April 2001\n|45\n|-\n|'''10'''\n|4 September 2001\n|29 December 2001\n|43\n|-\n|'''11'''\n|5 January 2002\n|9 April 2002\n|55\n|-\n|'''12'''\n|31 August 2002\n|28 December 2002\n|20\n|-\n|'''13'''\n|4 January 2003\n|31 May 2003\n|22\n|-\n|'''14'''\n|30 August 2003\n|27 December 2003\n|22\n|-\n|'''15'''\n|3 January 2004\n|5 June 2004\n|23\n|-\n|'''16'''\n|18 September 2004\n|25 December 2004\n|16\n|-\n|'''17'''\n|1 January 2005\n|11 June 2005\n|25\n|-\n|'''18'''\n|17 September 2005\n|31 December 2005\n|10\n|-\n|'''19'''\n|7 January 2006\n|8 July 2006\n|28\n|-\n|'''20'''\n|9 September 2006\n|6 January 2007\n|13\n|-\n|'''21'''\n|10 March 2007\n|28 July 2007\n|18\n|-\n|'''22'''\n|18 August 2007\n|30 October 2007\n|10\n|-\n|'''23'''\n|1 January 2008\n|3 June 2008\n|20\n|-\n|'''24'''\n|16 August 2008\n|31 January 2009\n|18\n|-\n|'''25'''\n|13 June 2009\n|20 December 2009\n|20\n|-\n|'''26'''\n|13 April 2010\n|8 June 2010\n|8\n|-\n|'''27'''\n|3 August 2010\n|23 December 2010\n|10\n|-\n|'''28'''\n|2 April 2011\n|19 December 2011\n|6\n|-\n|'''29'''\n|3 January 2012\n|20 December 2012\n|10\n|-\n|'''30'''\n|1 January 2013\n|11 February 2014\n|10\n|-\n|'''31'''\n|5 May 2018\n|11 May 2018\n|7\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Jeremy Clarkson]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''32'''\n| 1 January 2019\n| 6 January 2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |10\n|-\n|4 March 2019\n|8 March 2019\n|-\n|'''33'''\n|24 August 2019 \n|20 October 2019\n|10\n|-\n|'''34'''\n|25 December 2019\n|TBC 2020\n|12\n|}\n\n===Specials===\n*'''''Is that Your Final Answer?''''' \u2013 a one-hour documentary about the show, which aired on ITV on 24 December 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukchristmastv.weebly.com/itv-1999.html|title=ITV 1999|website=UK Christmas TV|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9xrMLC3tA0|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire \u2013 Is That Your Final Answer Documentary (1999)|first=|last=Coldclough|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Directed and produced by Robin Lough, it featured rare footage from the unaired pilot version of the programme, which has completely different music and behind the scenes footage from the programmes aired in Series 4 (September 1999). A similar documentary of the same name was also aired in Australia during 2000. A shorter half-hour Russian version was aired on 4 November 2000. Both of these primarily concentrated on their own versions of the show and featured the local hosts.\n*'''''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire Night''''' \u2013 a two-and-a-half-hour long special, which included parts of ''Is that Your Final Answer?'', that aired on digital channel [[ITV2]] in 2000. Hosted by Tarrant, it looked back on the first two years of the UK version, showing some of its best moments. It also looked at the original [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)|U.S.]] and [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (Australian game show)|Australian version]]s.\n*'''''Who Wants to Steal a Million?''''' \u2013 a two-hour documentary based on the [[Charles Ingram]] cheating scandal first broadcast on 9 June 2003, which features the major's full run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0370060/|title=Who Wants to Steal a Million?|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref> This was preceded by a special episode of ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'' which featured key segments of Ingram's run as well as interviews by the witnesses of the ensuing trial; the [[Martin Bashir]]-hosted documentary was broadcast on 21 April 2003 (before airing in the US on 8 May 2003 as a special episode of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Primetime (American TV program)|Primetime]]''). The documentary later aired on 15 February 2004, with subtitles, on [[HRT 2]] in Croatia. A special episode of the French version of ''Millionaire'', entitled \"''L'\u00e9mission interdite''\" (English translation: ''Prohibited episode''), was devoted to the scandal. This was broadcast on 1 July 2003 on [[TF1]].\n*'''''[[Quiz (TV series)|QUIZ]]''''' \u2013 A drama in three parts, each one hour in length, which aired on 13, 14 and 15 April 2020 and is based [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]]'s [[Quiz (TV series)|play of the same name]] which centres on the 2001 'cheating scandal'.\n\n== Text game (2004\u20132007) ==\nOn 23 October 2004 the show included a new feature called the \"Walkaway Text Game\". The competition was offered to viewers at home to play the text game where they had to answer the question, if a contestant decided to walk home with the cash prize they have got, by choosing the letters 'A, B, C or D' within 30 seconds to a specific mobile number. The viewer who answered the question won \u00a31,000 by having their entries selected randomly.\n\nOn 9 September 2006, there were some changes. The competition stayed the same but this time, they played it before some commercial breaks.  A question to which the contestant had given their final answer, but the correct answer had not yet been revealed, was offered as a competition to viewers. Entry was via [[SMS]] text message at a cost of \u00a31 per entry, and the competition ran through the commercial break, after which the answer was revealed and the game continued. One viewer who answered the question correctly won \u00a31,000. The text game ended on 28 July 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Millionaire\u2014Walkaway Game\n| publisher = itv.com\n| date =\n| url = http://millionaire.itv.com/millionaire/howtoplaywalkaway.php\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080724192629/http://millionaire.itv.com/millionaire/howtoplaywalkaway.php\n| archivedate = 24 July 2008\n| accessdate =25 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Incorrect answer to question accepted===\nOn 8 March 1999, contestant Tony Kennedy reached the \u00a364,000 question. He was asked \"Theoretically, what is the minimum number of strokes with which a [[tennis]] player can win a set?\", and given four possible answers \u2013 twelve, twenty-four, thirty-six, and forty-eight. Kennedy, who calculated that a player would need four shots to win a game, with six games in a set, answered twenty-four, and was told the answer was correct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDBNAIXmlEw&t=6m45s|title=Who Wants to be a Millionaire?  8th March 1999 Tony Kennedy|first=|last=James Booker|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the right answer was actually twelve and viewers quickly phoned up the show to complain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/293549.stm|title=Quiz 'winner' keeps his prize|date=9 March 1999|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> One such viewer, Robert Steadman, explained to ''[[The Irish Times]]'':\n:\"A tennis player needs six games to win a set. Let's assume he serves [[Ace (tennis)|aces]] for his three service games \u2013 four shots for three games which equals 12 strokes. Now, if his opponent [[Double fault (tennis)|double faults]] all their serves \u2013 so losing love 40 \u2013 the player hasn't had to make any strokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/man-scores-with-wrong-answer-1.160845|title=Man scores with wrong answer|date=9 March 1999|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe production staff acknowledged the mistake and apologised for it, but allowed Kennedy to keep his prize money (an eventual \u00a3125,000).<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n===Schedule rigging allegation===\nWhen [[Judith Keppel]]'s victory as the first UK jackpot winner on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was announced by ITV on the day of that the corresponding episode was to be broadcast, several allegations were made that [[Celador]] had rigged the show to spoil the BBC's expected high ratings for the [[Things Aren't Simple Any More|finale]] of ''[[One Foot in the Grave]]''.<ref name=\"w184\">{{harvnb|Webber|2006|p=184}}</ref> [[Richard Wilson (Scottish actor)|Richard Wilson]], the lead star on the sitcom, was quoted in particular for saying that the broadcaster had \"planned\" the win, adding \"it seems a bit unfair to take the audience away from Victor's last moments on earth.\"<ref name=\"wilson\">{{cite news |title=Wilson: Millionaire win 'planned' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1035069.stm |work=BBC News |date=22 November 2000 |accessdate=28 January 2007}}</ref> [[David Renwick]], writer of the sitcom, voiced annoyance that the episode would draw away interest from the sitcom's finale, believing that a leaked press release on ITV's announcement had been \"naked opportunism\", and it \"would have been more honourable to let the show go out in the normal way\", pointing out that it \"killed off any element of tension or surprise in their own programme\", but that \"television is all about ratings\".<ref name=\"w184\"/> Richard Webber's account, in his 2006 book, cites \"unnamed BBC sources\" as those who \"questioned the authenticity of Keppel's victory\".<ref name=\"w184\"/> The allegations, in turn, led to eleven viewers making complaints against the quiz show, of a similar nature, to the [[Independent Television Commission]] (ITC).<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |title=Millionaire? cleared of ratings 'fix' |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1118212.stm |date=15 January 2001 |accessdate=28 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn response, ITV expressed distress to the allegations, claiming that it \"undermined viewers' faith in the programme.\" Leslie Hill, the chairman of ITV, wrote to Sir [[Christopher Bland]], the chairman of the [[Board of Governors of the BBC]], to complain about the issue. The corporation apologised, saying that any suggestion of 'rigging' \"did not represent the official view of the BBC\",<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news |first=Terri |last=Judd |title=BBC apologises for 'Millionaire' dirty tricks slur |work=The Independent |date=2 December 2000 |location=London}}</ref> while the ITC's investigation cleared the programme of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"cleared\" /><ref name=\"casey\">{{harvnb|Casey|Calvert |2008|p=128}}</ref><ref name=\"bfi\">{{harvnb|Dyja|2002|p=20}}</ref>\n\n===Ambiguous question===\nOn 11 February 2006, celebrity couple [[Laurence Llewelyn-Bowen]] and his wife Jackie took on the game show to raise money for their chosen charity \u2013 The Shooting Star Children's Hospice. Having reached the final question of the quiz, they were asked \"Translated from the Latin, what is the motto of the United States?\", to which the Bowens answered with \"[[In God We Trust|In God, We Trust]]\", only to learn that the question's correct answer was \"One Out of Many\" \u2013 the English translation for the Latin ''[[E pluribus unum]]''.<ref name=\"secondchance\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4608690.stm|title=TV designer's second shot at \u00a31m |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=13 January 2006|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> However, Celador later admitted that the question had been ambiguous and not fair to the pair \u2013 although ''E pluribus unum'' is considered the de facto motto of the United States, it was never legally declared as such; ''In God, We Trust'' is the official motto of the country since 1956, although it is not translated from any form of Latin. Following this revelation, the production company invited the Bowens back to tackle a new question, with their original winnings reinstated; the couple chose not to risk the new question, and left with \u00a3500,000 for their charity.<ref name=\"secondchance\" />\n\n===Ingram cheating scandal===\n{{further|Charles Ingram#Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|l1=Charles Ingram \u2013 Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? scandal}}\n[[File:Charles Ingram 1.jpg|thumb|Charles Ingram and his wife Diana. Both had previously made appearances on the show, before Charles' controversial game in September 2001.]]\nIn September 2001, [[Major (United Kingdom)|British Army Major]] [[Charles Ingram]] became a contestant on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', joined by his wife Diana and a college lecturer, [[Tecwen Whittock]]. After the first day of filming, the group devised a scheme that would allow Ingram to win the \u00a31&nbsp;million cash prize when he returned for the second day of recording, on 10 September \u2013 for each question he faced, the correct answer would be signalled to Ingram by a cough made by Whittock;<ref name=\"Ingram Ploy\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm |title=Major Charles Ingram has been found guilty of cheating his way to the top prize on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 April 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Ingram would differentiate the way he received this to avoid making the scheme too obvious, such as reading aloud all four answers, or dismissing an answer and then choosing it again later.<ref name=\"Ingram Ploy\" /> Although the scheme proved successful, by the time he had reached the final questions, production staff off-stage had become suspicious over the amount of background noise being made by Whittock's coughing,<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2910119.stm|title=Millionaire trio escape jail|work=BBC News|date=8 April 2003|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> while noting that Ingram seemed to show no specialist knowledge of any subjects he faced with each question.\n\nAfter the second day of recording ended, the production staff ordered an immediate investigation on the grounds that cheating had occurred, suspending the broadcast of both episodes that had been filmed. Ingram was subsequently informed that he was being investigated for cheating and would not receive his winnings. While reviewing the recording, production staff began to see a pattern between Whittock's coughing, and Ingram's unusual behaviour when he answered questions;<ref name=\"FoundGuilty\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm|title=Millionaire's route to the top prize|date=7 April 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"devastated\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2964675.stm|title=Millionaire cheats left 'devastated'|date=21 April 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> at one point, they noticed Ingram gave an answer when Diana had coughed after he read it aloud. By this point,  production company [[Celador]] was convinced that cheating had occurred, and the matter was handed over to police. Both the Ingrams and Whittock were charged with \"procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception\", and taken to [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]] [[Crown Court]] in 2003.\n\nDuring the four-week long trial, the Prosecution provided evidence towards the charges, which included a recording of Ingram's second day on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', pager telephone records for a previous scheme the group intended to use,<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/uk/Pager-plot-too-risky-for.2408136.jp |title=Pager plot too risky for TV quiz |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=[[The Scotsman]] |first=John |last=Innes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022105328/http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/pager-plot-too-risky-for-tv-quiz-1-548871|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref> before deeming it too complicated \u2013 a system of four pagers intended to be hidden on Ingram's body, in which a pager's vibrations signalled the correct answer \u2013 and testimony from one of the production staff and a \"Fastest Finger\" contestant attending the recording, Larry Whitehurst.<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /><ref name=\"BBC News\u2013Coughs\">{{cite news|title=Contestant 'spotted Millionaire coughs'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2839587.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 July 2011|date=11 March 2003}}</ref> Although the Defence provided evidence claiming Whittock's coughing was a result of dust allergies and a hay fever he was suffering from, and Whittock himself testified against the accusations,<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weekend/story/0,3605,938649,00.html |title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part two |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 April 2003 |location=London |work=The Guardian}}</ref> the Prosecution refuted these claims with their evidence, including footage that showed Whittock stopped coughing when he became a contestant after Ingram.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> On 7 April 2003, the group were found guilty, with all three given [[suspended sentence|suspended prison sentences]] and fines, with the Ingrams later ordered to pay legal costs within two months of the trial's conclusion.<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /> On 24 July 2003, the British Army ordered Charles Ingram to resign his commission as a Major, in the wake of the trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3092357.stm|title=Millionaire cheat sacked by Army|date=24 July 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the trial, the scandal became the subject of an ITV documentary entitled ''Millionaire: A Major Fraud'' (aired as an edition of ''[[Tonight with Trevor McDonald]]'') presented by [[Martin Bashir]] and broadcast on 21 April 2003, with a follow-up two weeks later entitled ''Millionaire: The Final Answer''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/apr/22/1|title=The cough carries it off|last=Day|first=Julian|date=22 April 2003|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> The documentary featured excerpts from the recording that had been enhanced for the Ingrams' trial, footage of the actions made by Ingram's wife in the audience, and interviews with production staff and some of the contestants who had been present during the recording. None of the defendants in the case took part, with Ingram later describing ''Major Fraud'' and a subsequent programme of the matter, shown on [[ITV2]], as \"one of the greatest TV editing con tricks in history\". Chess grandmaster [[James Plaskett]] later wrote an essay arguing in favour of the group's innocence;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://millionaire3.blogspot.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822075317/http://www.themillionairethree.com/|url-status=dead|title=Millionaire Three \u2013 The Rich, The Poor And Inbetween|archivedate=22 August 2012}}</ref> journalists [[Bob Woffinden]], and [[Jon Ronson]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Are the Millionaire three innocent?|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 July 2006|url=http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/jon_ronson/2006/07/could_the_who_wants_to_be_a_mi.html|accessdate=25 September 2007 |location=London |first=Jon |last=Ronson |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109152611/http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/jon_ronson/2006/07/could_the_who_wants_to_be_a_mi.html|archivedate=19 November 2007}}</ref> each wrote a piece influenced by this essay, with Woffinden collaborating with Plaskett on a book entitled ''Bad Show: The Quiz, The Cough, The Millionaire Major'', published in 2015, arguing that Ingram's appearance on the show coinciding with Whittock's was \"chance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/552631/Coughing-cheat-Who-Wants-to-be-a-Millionaire-was-innocent|title='Coughing Major' was INNOCENT of cheating on Who Wants to be a Millionaire, says new book|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Winchester|first=Levi|date=17 January 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> A play based upon the events of the scandal was written by [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]], entitled ''[[Quiz (play)|Quiz]]'', and was performed from 3 November 2017 to 9 December 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cft.org.uk/whats-on/event/quiz |title=Quiz |accessdate=18 November 2017 |publisher=Chichester Festival Theatre}}</ref> before being performed in the West End from 31 March 2018 to 16 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412123518/http://quiztheplay.com/|title=Quiz the Play by James Graham {{!}} Official West End Website|date=12 April 2018|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>Following the success of the West End performance, Quiz, ITV commissioned a new 3 part drama based on the cheating scandal also titled 'Quiz' and written by James Graham which is set to air in the UK on  13, 14 and 15 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itvmedia.co.uk/making-an-impact/itv-has-commissioned-quiz-a-three-part-drama-directed-by-stephen-frears-starring-hollywood-star-michael-sheen|title=ITV has commissioned 'Quiz' directed by Stephen Frears starring Hollywood star, Michael Sheen|website=ITV Media|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===Phone-a-Friend===\nThe Phone-a-Friend lifeline provided multiple instances of controversy during the show's run. A 2002 edition of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' reported that many contestants had selected strangers who were \"contacts among the quizzing fraternity\"<ref>[[#Woffinden|Woffinden; Plaskett]], p.55</ref> to act as their Phone-a-Friends. Specifically, game show champion [[Daphne Fowler]] was approached by a man she had not previously met and asked if she would be his lifeline in exchange for \u00a3200. Fowler refused, adding: \"I thought a fair price would be a quarter of whatever the man won, so if I helped him get from \u00a332,000 to \u00a364,000 I would expect to get \u00a316,000.\"<ref name=\"Fowler\">{{cite news|last=Conlan|first=Tara|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-110267/Ill-phone-stranger.html|title=I'll phone a stranger|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=18 April 2002|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}} The man was later revealed by ITV sources not to have made it onto the programme.<ref name=\"Fowler\"/>\n\nIn March 2007 various UK newspapers reported that an organised syndicate had been getting quiz enthusiasts onto the show in return for a percentage of their winnings. The person behind the syndicate was Keith Burgess from Northern Ireland. Burgess admitted to helping around 200 contestants to appear on the show since 1999; he estimates those contestants to have won around \u00a35,000,000. The show producers are believed to have been aware of this operation, with Burgess stating: \"The show knows about me and these types of syndicates, but they cover it up to keep the show going.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Phoney a Friend|work=[[Sunday Mirror]]|date=18 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quiz syndicate leader denies wrongdoing|publisher=crewechronicle.co.uk|date=23 March 2007|url=http://www.crewechronicle.co.uk/news/local-news/quiz-syndicate-leader-denies-wrongdoing-5636037|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> An earlier version of a Phone a Friend syndicate was reported in the ''Northampton Chronicle and Echo'' during 2003.<ref name=\"Northampton\">{{cite news|title=Millionaire syndicate is probed|publisher=northamptonchron.co.uk|date=23 April 2003|url=http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/millionaire-syndicate-is-probed-1-888831|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> Paul Smith, the managing director of Celador Productions, stated: \"We are aware of Paddy Spooner and what people similar to him are doing, and we have made a priority of changing our question procedure. We are confident we have now made it impossible for anyone to manipulate the system.\"<ref name=\"Northampton\" /> Since then, the options of people that can be called have a picture of themselves shown on-air. During the 2010-14 era, and with the show's relaunch in 2018 every person listed as a friend who might be called had a person from the production company present to video their actions.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Filming locations==\nSince airing in September 1998, ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' has been filmed at 3 locations throughout its 21-year run. It was first filmed at the now-defunct [[Fountain Studios]] in London from its inception until the end of the third series which aired in March 1999. It then moved to [[Elstree Studios]], also in London, in preparation for series 4, which aired in September 1999. Elstree was the home of '' Millionaire '' right up until the end of its initial run in February 2014. For the show\u2019s revival in 2018 and all subsequent episodes, filming moved to [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] in Manchester.\n\n*Fountain Studios \u2013 Series 1\u20133 (36 episodes)\n*Elstree Studios \u2013 Series 4\u201330 (556 episodes)\n*dock10 studios \u2013 Series 31\u2013present (32 episodes)\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |first1=Bernadette |last1=Casey |first2=Ben |last2=Calvert |title=Television Studies: The Key Concepts |publisher=Routledge |location=London |year=2008 |edition=2 |isbn=978-0-415-37149-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-first=Eddie |editor1-last=Dyja |title=BFI Film and Television Handbook 2002 |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London |year=2002|isbn=978-0-85170-904-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Richard |last=Webber |title=The Complete One Foot in the Grave |publisher=Orion |location=London |year=2006|isbn=978-0-7528-7357-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=Woffinden|first1=Bob|last1=Woffinden|first2=James|last2=Plaskett|title=Bad Show: The Quiz, the Cough, the Millionaire Major|publisher=Bojangles Books|year=2015|isbn=978-0-9930755-2-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.millionaire-show.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0166064|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK)}}\n* {{UKGameshow|Who_Wants_to_be_a_Millionaire%3F|Who Wants to be a Millionaire?}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? (British game show)}}\n[[Category:1998 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2000s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2010s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s British game shows]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:ITV game shows]]\n[[Category:Carlton Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Steven Knight]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the original UK version|the international franchise|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = {{nowrap|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?}}\n| image                    = WWTBAM20thTitle.png\n| caption                  = Titlecard for the revived series of the show (20th anniversary version)\n| genre                    = [[Quiz show]]\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* David Briggs\n* [[Steven Knight|Steve Knight]]\n* Mike Whitehill\n}}\n| presenter                = <!--No years or seasons as per template-->{{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris Tarrant]] <small>(1998\u20132014)</small> \n* [[Jeremy Clarkson]] <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Keith Strachan]] <small>(1998\u20132007{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}, 2018\u2013present)</small> \n* [[Matthew Strachan]] <small>(1998\u20132007{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}, 2018\u2013present)</small> \n* Ramon Covalo <small>(2007\u201314) </small>\n</small>\n}}\n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language                 = [[English language|English]]\n| num_series               = 34\n| num_episodes             = 625 <!--as of Sunday 5 Jan 2020-->\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fountain Studios]] <small>(1998\u20131999)</small>\n* [[Elstree Studios]] <small>(1999\u20132014)</small>\n* [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| runtime                  = 30\u201380 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Celador]] <small>(1998\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Carlton Television|Carlton]] <small>(1998)</small>\n* [[2waytraffic]] <small>(2007\u201310)</small>\n* [[Sony Pictures Television|Victory Television]] <small>(2011\u201314)</small>\n* [[Stellify Media]] <small>(2018\u2013)</small>\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Celador International]]/[[2waytraffic|2waytraffic International]] (1998\u20132009)<br>[[Sony Pictures Television International|Sony Pictures Television International Distribution]] (2009\u2013present)\n| producer                 = Fiona Clark (as of 2018 revival)\n| network                  = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| picture_format           = [[4:3]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small><br>[[16:9]] <small>(1999\u2013)</small>\n| first_aired              = '''Original series:'''<br>{{Start date|1998|9|4|df=y}}&nbsp;\u2013 {{end date|2014|2|11|df=y}}<br>'''Revived series:'''<br> {{Start date|2018|5|5|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.millionaire-show.com/\n}}\n\n'''''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''''' is a British television quiz show, created and produced by David Briggs, and made for the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] network. On air since September 1998 and devised by Briggs, the show's format sees contestants taking on multiple-choice questions based upon general knowledge, winning a cash prize for each question they answer correctly, with the amount offered increasing as they take on more difficult questions. To assist each contestant who takes part, they are given lifelines to use, may walk away with the money they already have won if they wish not to risk answering a question, and are provided with a safety net that gives them a guaranteed cash prize if they give an incorrect answer, provided they reach a specific milestone in the quiz.\n\nThe original series aired for 30 series and aired a total of 592 episodes, from 4 September 1998 to 11 February 2014, and was presented by [[Chris Tarrant]]. Over the course of its initial run, the show had five contestants achieve the show\u2019s ultimate aim and walk away with the cash prize of \u00a31&nbsp;million. The original format of the programme was tweaked in later years; this included changing the number of questions from fifteen to twelve, altering the payout structure and later incorporating a time limit which included an attainable fourth lifeline. There were several controversies during its run, including an attempt by a contestant to [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|defraud the show of its top prize]].\n\nFour years after the original series ended, ITV announced that the series would be revived, this time produced by [[Stellify Media]], to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the programme. The revival was based closely on the show\u2019s original format. It was hosted by [[Jeremy Clarkson]] and filmed at [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10 studios]]. The success of the revival series has ensured that subsequent series of the show have been commissioned, and in January 2019 the show reached the milestone of 600 episodes since first appearing on air.\n\nThe game show became one of the most significant shows in British popular culture, ranking 23rd in a list of the [[BFI TV 100|100 Greatest British Television Programmes]] compiled in 2000 by the [[British Film Institute]]. It was the highest quiz programme to appear on the list. Its success led to versions in [[International versions of Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|many other countries]] under an [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|international franchise of the same name]], all of which follow the same general format, though with some versions including unique differences in gameplay and lifelines provided.\n\n==History==\n{{Multiple image\n| direction = horizontal\n| width =\n| align = right\n| header = UK presenters of ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''\n| image1 = Chris Tarrant Phooto.jpg\n| image2 = Jeremy Clarkson.jpg\n| width1 = 130\n| width2 = 135\n| caption1 = [[Chris Tarrant]] (1998\u20132014)\n| caption2 = [[Jeremy Clarkson]] (2018\u2013present)\n| alt1 = Tarrant\n| alt2 = Clarkson\n}}\n\n===Creation===\nThe creation of the game show was led by David Briggs, assisted by Mike Whitehill and Steven Knight, who had helped him before with creating a number of promotional games for Chris Tarrant's [[Capital Breakfast|morning show]] on [[95.8 Capital FM|Capital FM]] radio. The basic premise for the show was a twist on the conventional game-show genre of the time, with a focus towards the setup used in radio quizzes, in that the programme would have one contestant taking on the game and answering questions, but with the ability to pull out at any time, to have certain points in the quiz where once passed, they could have a set prize given to them if they should give a wrong answer, and be provided with special forms of assistance during their game. During the design phase, the show was given the [[working title]] of \"Cash Mountain\", before Briggs decided upon using the name of the [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (song)|song]] written by [[Cole Porter]] for the 1956 film ''[[High Society (1956 film)|High Society]]'', as the show's finalised title.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> After presenting their idea to [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], the broadcaster gave the green-light for production to begin on a series.\n\nThe set designed for ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was conceived by British [[production designer]] [[Andy Walmsley]], who focused the design towards making contestants feel uncomfortable, creating an atmosphere of tension similar to [[Thriller film|movie thriller]].<ref name=\"Walmsley\">{{Cite web|title=Millionaire|url=http://www.andywalmsley.com/millionaire.php|publisher=Andy Walmsley, Production Designer|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> The design was in stark contrast to the design of sets made for more typical game shows, which are designed to make contestants feel more at ease.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> Walmsley's design feature a central stage made primarily with [[Plexiglas]], with a huge dish underneath covered in mirror paper,<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/><ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> onto which two slightly-modified, {{convert|3|foot|m}}-high Pietranera Arco All chairs were chosen for use by both the contestant and the host, each having an [[LG Electronics|LG]] computer monitor directly facing each that would be used to display questions and other pertinent information. The rest of the set featured seating spaced out around the main stage in a circle, with breaks in them to allow movement of people on and off the set. The lighting rig used for the set was designed so as to allow only the lights to switch from illuminating the entire set, to focusing on the host and contestant on the main stage when a game was underway, but to include special lighting effects when the contestant reached higher cash prize amounts. His overall conception would eventually prove to be a success, becoming one of the most reproduced scenic designs in television history.<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/>\n\nThe music provided for the show was composed by father-and-son duo [[Keith Strachan|Keith]] and [[Matthew Strachan]]. The Strachans' composition for the game show helped with Briggs' tense game design, by providing the necessary drama and tension. Unlike other game show musical scores, the music provided for ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was designed to be played throughout the entire episode of the show. The Strachans main theme for the game show was inspired from the \"Mars\" movement of [[Gustav Holst]]'s ''[[The Planets]]''. For the main game of the show, the pair designed the music to feature three variations, with the second and third compositions focused on emphasising the increased tension of the game \u2013 as a contestant made progress to higher cash amounts, the pitch of the music was increased by a semitone for each subsequent question.<ref name=\"Million Dollar Notes\">{{cite news|title=Million Pound Notes: Keith Strachan|last=Smurthwaite|first=Nick|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=21 March 2005|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612081217/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archivedate=12 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> On [[Game Show Network]]'s ''Gameshow Hall of Fame'' special, the narrator described the Strachan tracks as \"mimicking the sound of a beating heart\", and stated that as the contestant works their way up the money ladder, the music is \"perfectly in tune with their ever-increasing pulse\".<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\">{{Cite episode|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|series=Gameshow Hall of Fame|publisher=GSN|date=21 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Original series===\nWith the show created, ITV assigned [[Chris Tarrant]] as its host, and set its premiere to 4 September 1998. The programme was assigned a timeslot of one hour, to provide room for three commercial breaks, with episodes produced by UK production company [[Celador]]. Originally, the show was broadcast on successive evenings for around ten days, before the network modified its broadcast schedule in autumn 2000<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/29/broadcasting3|title=Millionaire ratings slide|first=Jason|last=Deans|date=29 November 2001|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> to air it within a primetime slot on Saturday evenings, with occasional broadcasts on Tuesday evenings. ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' proved a ratings hit, pulling in average viewing figures of up to 19 million during its broadcast in 1999 (all-time high was on 7 March 1999, 19.2 million viewers),<ref name=\"auto\"/> though such figures often occurred when the programme was allocated to a half-hour timeslot. By September 2000 viewing figures had dropped to 11.1 million viewers,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and by 2003 to an average of around 8&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Millionaire: A TV phenomenon|work=BBC News|date=3 March 2003|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2783505.stm|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Audiences continued to drop<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2004/jan/26/overnights|title=TV ratings: January 23\u201324|first=Claire|last=Cozens|date=26 January 2004|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> and from 2005 to 2011 the show usually attracted between 3 and 4 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/03/ITV.overnights|title=TV ratings: April 30|first=Julia|last=Day|date=3 May 2005|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jan/23/tvratings.television|title=TV ratings \u2013 January 22: Ladettes fail to attract viewers to ITV|first=Leigh|last=Holmwood|date=23 January 2008|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/01/the-bill-finale-tv-ratings|title=The Bill finale wins 4.4m viewers &#124; TV ratings \u2013 31 August|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=1 September 2010|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> At one point in September 1999, an episode had 60% of the TV share and caused the [[BBC]] an historic low in ratings.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Over the course of his time presenting the game show, Tarrant developed a number of notable catchphrases, including \"Is that your final answer?\", \"But we don't want to give you that\" and \"Audience, all on your keypads please. All Vote Now!\" with the latter often used to emphasise his wish to see contestants continue on and win more money and audience allowed to vote the answers in the lifeline used.\n\nSince its launch, several individuals made claims over the origins of the format or elements of it, with each accusing Celador of breaching their copyrights. In three cases, the matters could not be proven by the claimants \u2013 in 2002, Mike Bull, a [[Southampton]]-based journalist, was given an out-of-court settlement when he claimed the authorship of lifelines was his work, though with a confidentiality clause attached; in 2003, Sydney resident John J. Leonard made claims in that the show's format was based on one he had made of a similar nature, but without the concept of lifelines;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xavierax.com/ebook.pdf |title=Millionaire 2nd Edition.qxd |format=PDF |last=Leonard |first=John J. |year=2005 |accessdate=2 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801163453/http://www.xavierax.com/ebook.pdf |archive-date=1 August 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The show that should have made me a million|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/03/29/1048653901387.html|first=Daniel |last=Dasey|newspaper=The Sydney Sun-Herald|date=30 March 2003}}</ref> in 2004, Alan Melville was given an out-of-court settlement after he claimed that the opening phrase \"Who wants to be a millionaire?\" had been taken from a document he sent to [[Granada Television]], concerning his idea for a game show based on the lottery.\n\nOne of most significant claims Celador received against them was from John Bachini. In 2002, he started legal proceedings against the production company, ITV, and five individuals who had claimed they had created ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', stating that the idea from the show was taken from several elements he had created \u2013 a board game format he conceived in 1981; a two-page TV format, known as ''Millionaire'', made in 1987; and the telephone mechanics for a TV concept he created in 1989, ''BT Lottery''. In his claim, Bachini stated that he submitted documents for his TV concepts to Paul Smith, from a sister company of Celador's, in March 1995 and again in January 1996, and to [[Claudia Rosencrantz]] of ITV, also in January 1996, accusing both of using roughly 90% of the format for ''Millionaire'' in the pilot for the game show, including the use of twenty questions, lifelines and safety nets, although the lifelines were conceived under different names \u2013 Bachini claimed that he never coined the phrase \"phone-a-friend\" that Briggs designed in his format. In response to this claim, Celador made a counter-claim that the franchise originated from the basic format idea conceived by Briggs. The defendants in the claim took Bachini to a summary hearing but lost their right to have his claim dismissed. Although Bachini won the right to go to trial, he was unable to after the hearing due to serious illness. Celador eventually settled the matter with him out-of-court.<ref>[http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/sundaymercury/news/tm_objectid=15908484&method=full&siteid=50002&headline=who-wants-to-sue-a-millionaire-name_page.html Birmingham Sunday Mercury], 28 August 2005</ref>\n\nIn March 2006, Celador began procedures to sell the format of the show and all UK episodes, as part of their first step towards the sale of their formats divisions. The purchase of both assets was made by Dutch company [[2waytraffic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toynews-online.biz/news/read/new-owners-take-on-celador-international-and-millionaire-brand/039482|title=New owners take on Celador International and Millionaire brand|publisher=toynews-online.biz|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|date=1 December 2006|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref> which were then passed on to [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] in 2008 when it acquired 2waytraffic.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2008/more/news/sony-pictures-acquires-2waytraffic-1117986861/|title=Sony Pictures acquires 2waytraffic|magazine=Variety|last=Levine|first=Stuart|date=4 June 2008|accessdate=19 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308125215/http://variety.com/2008/scene/news/sony-pictures-acquires-2waytraffic-1117986861/|archivedate=8 March 2014}}</ref> As the original series progressed, variations of the format were created, and screened as special episodes, including celebrity editions, games featuring couples as contestants, and episodes themed around special events such as Mother's Day.\n\nThe Christmas Eve celebrity special from December 2010 drew its biggest audience since 2006. To capitalise on this, and breathe new life into the now 12-year-old show,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/12/itv-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire|title=ITV looks to revive Millionaire's sparkle|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=12 January 2011|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> from April 2011 only celebrity contestants appeared on the show, in special live editions that coincided with holidays, events and other notable moments, such as the end of a [[school term]]. However, in 2012, three special episodes, entitled \"The People Play\", were broadcast for three consecutive nights between 9 and 11 July. They featured standard contestants, with viewers at home allowed to play along.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millionaire.itv.com/be-a-contestant/ |title=This summer, Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? will once again be going live, but this time with the Great British public in the hotseat! |publisher=ITV |accessdate=7 November 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530075910/http://millionaire.itv.com/be-a-contestant/|archivedate=30 May 2012}}</ref> The special was used three more times in 2013, once on 7 May, and twice more on 21 May, before the special's format was discontinued.\n\nOn 22 October 2013, Tarrant announced that, after fifteen years of hosting the programme, he would be leaving ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', which consequently led ITV to axe the programme once his contract was finished; no more specials would be filmed after this announcement, leaving only those made before it to be aired as the final episodes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/who-wants-millionaire-axed-host-2479545 |title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire axed as host Chris Tarrant decided 'it was time to take a break' |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.u.tv/entertainment/Millionaire-axed-as-Tarrant-quits/73946d68-1f14-4ad2-9d20-912ca13e275c |title=Millionaire axed as Tarrant quits |website=[[UTV Media|u.tv]] |accessdate=22 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022152601/http://www.u.tv/entertainment/Millionaire-axed-as-Tarrant-quits/73946d68-1f14-4ad2-9d20-912ca13e275c |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> After a few more celebrity editions of the game show, Tarrant hosted his final episode, a [[clip show]] entitled \"Chris' Final Answer\", which aired on 11 February 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-chriss-final-answer-tv-review-tarrant-isnt-quite-on-the-money-with-9122226.html|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Chris's Final Answer \u2013 TV review: 'Tarrant isn't quite on the money'|date=12 February 2014|first=Ellen |last=Jones|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Revival===\nIn 2018, ITV revived the show for a new series, as part of its 20th anniversary commemorations of the programme. On 23 February, the broadcast put out a casting call for contestants who would appear on the game show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/beontv/shows/whowantstobeamillionaire|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?|date=23 February 2018|publisher=itv.com|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> On 9 March, [[Jeremy Clarkson]] was confirmed as the new host of the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43342726|title=Jeremy Clarkson replaces Chris Tarrant on Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?|work=BBC News|date=9 March 2018}}</ref> On 13 April, the trailer for the revival premiered on ITV and confirmed that the show would return in May for a week-long run.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a854690/jeremy-clarkson-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-itv-revival-trailer/|title=ITV releases trailer for Jeremy Clarkson's Who Wants to Be a Millionaire revival|last=Lee|first=Ben|date=13 April 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Shows aired from 5 May to 11 May and were filmed in Studio HQ2 at [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] in [[Greater Manchester]]. The first episode drew an average of 5.06 million viewers, a 29.7% TV share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/956427/Who-Wants-To-Be-A-Millionaire-Jeremy-Clarkson-Chris-Tarrant-Ratings-Viewers-Comparison-ITV|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire: Jeremy Clarkson and Chris Tarrant\u2019s ratings war REVEALED|first=Rory|last=O'Connor|date=7 May 2018|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nITV renewed the show for another series, with Clarkson returning as host. It aired for 6 episodes from 1 to 6 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? returns to ITV in 2019 |url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/who-wants-be-millionaire-returns-itv-2019 |website=www.ITV.com |accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> The second half of the second series began on 4 March 2019 with 5 episodes. The third series began on 24 August 2019 with 11 episodes with the episodes airing like the old format once weekly.\n\nITV then renewed a fourth series for a celebrity edition of the show, with Clarkson returning as host and showing 4 episodes airing on 25 December 2019, (a Christmas Special), 4 January 2020, 5 January and 12 April. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week52/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 1|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep2week2/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 2|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep3week2/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 3|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week16/who-wants-be-millionaire-celebrity-special|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? Celebrity Special Episode 1|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Top prize winners===\nOver the course of the programme's broadcast history, it has had five (six if [[Charles Ingram]] was counted) winners who received its top prize of \u00a31 million. They are:\n\n* [[Judith Keppel]],<ref>Charles Mosley (ed.), ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage'' (London: Burke's Peerage, 1999)</ref> a former garden designer. On 20 November 2000, she became the first contestant to win the top prize. Following her success, Keppel later went onto become part of team of quiz experts for the BBC game show, ''[[Eggheads (TV series)|Eggheads]]''.\n* [[David Edwards (Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? contestant)|David Edwards]], a former physics teacher of [[Cheadle High School]] and [[Denstone College]] in [[Staffordshire]]. On 21 April 2001, he became the second contestant to win the top prize. Following his success, Edwards went on to compete in both series of ''[[Are You an Egghead?]]'', in 2008 and 2009 respectively, but failed to win either series and secure a place as a panellist on ''Eggheads''.\n*Charles Ingram, a former [[British army]] [[major]] in [[Shardlow]], [[Derbyshire]]. On 10 September 2001, he became the third person to win the top prize. Due to his actions on the show and being suspended in his trial, he didn't actually became the third person to win the top prize.\n* Robert Brydges,<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1566029.stm|title=Fourth Millionaire 'is millionaire'|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 August 2014|date=29 September 2001}}</ref> an [[Oxford]]-educated banker from [[Holland Park]], [[London]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1358013/Millionaire-quiz-show-aims-to-broaden-appeal.html|title='Millionaire' quiz show aims to broaden appeal|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=1 August 2013|location=London}}</ref> On 29 September 2001, he became the third (fourth if Charles was counted) person to win the show's top prize.<!-- Regardless of some Ref titles say, he was the third million pound winner, .--><ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a3888/fourth-contestant-wins-millionaire.html|title=Fourth contestant wins 'Millionaire'|website=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"thefreelibrary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/THANKS+A+MILLION..+WE'RE+BOTH+WINNERS%3b+EXCLUSIVE%3a+Couple+each+scoop...-a078293637|title=THANKS A MILLION.. WE'RE BOTH WINNERS; EXCLUSIVE: Couple each scoop TV prize.|publisher=[[Free Online Library]]|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2003/apr/19/weekend7.weekend6|title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part one|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Pat Gibson]], a multiple world champion Irish quiz player. On 24 April 2004, he became the fourth (fifth if Charles was counted) person to win the top prize.\n* [[Ingram Wilcox]], a British [[quiz]] enthusiast. On 23 September 2006, he became the fifth (sixth if Charles was counted) person to win the top prize.\n\n==Format==\n\n===Auditioning===\n\nDuring the original run, members of the public who wished to apply for the game show were provided with four options to choose from \u2013 calling/texting a premium-rate number; submitting an application via the show's ITV website, using a system of \u00a31 \u2018credits\u2019, or taking part in a casting audition, which were held at various locations around the UK. Once an application was made, production staff selected an episode's contestants through a combination of random selection, and a potential contestant's ability to answer a set of test questions based on general knowledge.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===Game rules=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right\"\t\n|-\t\n!colspan=4 style=\"background: #58B9E4\"| Payout structure\t\n|-\t\n!rowspan=2| Question<br>number\t\n!colspan=3| Question value\t\n|-\t\n! 1998\u20132007; 2018\u2013present\t\n! 2007\u20132014\t\n|-\t\n| 1\t\n| \u00a3100\t\n| \u00a3500\t\t\n|-\t\n| 2\t\n| \u00a3200\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a31,000'''\t\n|-\t\n| 3\t\n| \u00a3300\t\n| \u00a32,000\t\n|-\t\n| 4\t\n| \u00a3500\t\n| \u00a35,000\t\n|-\t\n| 5\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a31,000'''\t\n| \u00a310,000\t\n|-\t\n| 6\t\n| \u00a32,000\t\n| \u00a320,000\t\n|-\t\n| 7\t\n| \u00a34,000\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a350,000'''\t\n|-\t\n| 8\t\n| \u00a38,000\t\n| \u00a375,000\t\n|-\t\n| 9\t\n| \u00a316,000\t\n| \u00a3150,000\t\n|-\t\n| 10\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''\u00a332,000'''\t\n| \u00a3250,000\t\n|-\t\n| 11\t\n| \u00a364,000\t\n| \u00a3500,000\t\n|-\t\n| 12\t\n| \u00a3125,000\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''''\u00a31,000,000'''''\t\n|-\t\n| 13\t\n| \u00a3250,000\t\n| rowspan=3 {{N/A}}\t\n|-\t\n| 14\t\n| \u00a3500,000\n|-\t\n| 15\t\n| style=\"background: #FFE600\"| '''''\u00a31,000,000'''''\t\n|-\n\t\n|}\n\nOnce contestants auditioned for a part on the programme and filming took place, they undertook a preliminary round entitled \"Fastest Finger First\". Initially, the round required contestants to provide the correct answer to a question, but from series 2 onwards, they were tasked with putting four answers in the correct order stated within the question (i.e. earliest to latest). The contestant who answered the question correctly, and in the fastest time, won the opportunity to play the main game. In the event that no one answered the question correctly, a new question was asked, while if two or more contestants gave the correct answer in the same time, there was a tiebreaker question to determine who proceeded to the main game. The round was primarily used to determine the next contestant for the main game, and was more often than not used more than once in an episode.\n\nUpon completion of the preliminary round, the contestant began the main game, tackling a series of increasingly difficult questions, which offered progressively higher sums of money, up to the top prize of \u00a31,000,000. The stacks of 15 questions were randomly chosen from a list of pre generated questions based on general knowledge. For each question there were four options to choose from, labelled \u2018A\u2019, \u2018B\u2019, \u2018C\u2019 and \u2018D\u2019. During the game, contestants were allowed to use a set of 3 lifelines to help them with a question at any time, and two monetary safety nets were provided: if a contestant got a question wrong, but had reached a designated cash value during their game, they left with that amount as their prize. If a contestant was unsure about a question they were facing, they were allowed to leave the game at that point with the cash amount they had already won. While the initial questions were typically generally easy, the subsequent ones after it required the contestant to confirm that their answer/decision is final, at which point it became locked in and could not be reversed. As a rule, host Tarrant was not shown the correct answer on his monitor until a contestant had given their final answer. If an episode had reached the end of its allotted time, an audio cue was triggered to highlight this; contestants who were still playing the main game were left to wait until filming for the next episode began before they could continue, though this was not the case for special editions of the show, such as celebrity episodes.\n\nOver the course of the show's history on British television, the format of the programme has been altered in a number of aspects, mainly towards the setup of questions and the payout structure used in the game show, along with minor tweaks and changes in other aspects:\n* Between September 1998 and July 2007, contestants had to answer 15 questions, with two safety nets placed at \u00a31,000 and \u00a332,000, and they were allowed three standard lifelines.\n* Between August 2007 and February 2014, the number of questions was reduced to 12, with most cash values adjusted. This alteration led to the second safety net being assigned to \u00a350,000.\n* From the start of the 27th series in August 2010, the format was changed to include a clock format, similar to the 2008\u201310 US version, but with some differences. The time limit was 15 seconds for the first two questions, and 30 seconds for the next five questions, but the last five questions had no time limit. The clock would start ticking down as soon as the answers appeared on screen, and the contestant would have to give his/her final answer within the time limit. If they ran out of time it was treated as an incorrect answer. The clock would briefly pause, however, if any lifeline was used. It also added a new, fourth lifeline, Switch, which would be made available after passing question seven. The first episode of this series also saw the discontinuation of 'Fastest Finger First' for the first time since the inception of the show, so the contestants were then pre-selected by the production staff.\n* For the revival in 2018 and subsequent series of the show, the show returned to the 1998\u20132007 format, including the original payout structure and fastest finger process, with minor differences. A new lifeline, \u2018Ask The Host\u2019, was introduced and the placement of the second safety net could be set by the contestant. Upon reaching \u00a31,000, the contestant would be asked before each subsequent question if they would like to set the safety net to the cash value, with it offered up to question 14, \u00a3500,000. The number of contestants for 'Fastest Finger First' were also reduced from ten to six.\n* At the end of the allotted time of each standard episode, a loud sound (one long brass note) indicates the end of the show. The host refers to this noise as the \u2018klaxon\u2019. During the live specials whilst Tarrant was host, the contestant's game would end and any question in play would be null and void unless they gave a final answer before the klaxon sounded. The contestant\u2019s game then carries on at the start of the next episode.\n\n===Lifelines===\nDuring a contestant's game, they may make use of a set of lifelines to provide assistance on a question. Each lifeline may only be used once. Throughout the course of the show's history, these lifelines involve the following:\n* '''50:50''': Two random incorrect answers are eliminated by the computer, leaving the correct answer and the one remaining incorrect answer, thus granting the contestant a 50/50 chance of answering the question correctly.\n* '''Phone a Friend''': The contestant calls one of their friends, and has 30 seconds to read the question and answers to them. The friend uses the leftover time to offer an answer. Since 2011, a member of the production team accompanies the friend to prevent cheating, such as using the Internet or reading books. Since the revival in 2018, host Jeremy Clarkson makes sure this is carried out over each phone a friend phone call by asking the contestant\u2019s phone a friend to confirm that a member of the production office is present to record them and ensure no form of cheating occurs.\n* '''Ask the Audience''': Audience members use keypads to vote on what they believe to be the correct answer to the question they\u2019ve been asked. The percentage of each option selected by the audience is displayed to the contestant after this vote, as well as appearing on TV.\n* '''Switch/Flip''' (2002\u201303, 2010\u201314): The computer replaces one question with another of the same monetary value. Any lifelines already used on the original question are not reinstated. In its original run, Switch was originally called \"Flip\" and could only be used if the contestant chose to trade in one of their unused lifelines for it, using it up to three times. From 2010 to 2014, this lifeline was separated and became available after the contestant answered seven questions correctly.\n* '''Ask the Host''' (2018\u2013present): Host Jeremy Clarkson offers advice or an answer to the question he is asked. This lifeline can also be used just once. He must disclose that he has no contact with outside sources and there is no time limit as to how long he can offer help. On this question, the answer does not reveal itself to the host when the contestant plays; instead, the computer reveals the answer to the host and contestant at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/who-wants-be-millionaire-returns-itv-saturday-brand-new-twists|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? returns to ITV this Saturday with brand new twists|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n===Main series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Series\n!Start date\n!End date\n!Episodes\n!Presenter\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|4 September 1998\n|25 December 1998\n|10\n| rowspan=\"30\" |[[Chris Tarrant]]\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|1 January 1999\n|13 January 1999\n|13\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|5 March 1999\n|16 March 1999\n|12\n|-\n|'''4'''\n|3 September 1999\n|14 September 1999\n|13\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|5 November 1999\n|25 December 1999\n|18\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|16 January 2000\n|22 January 2000\n|7\n|-\n|'''7'''\n|26 March 2000\n|1 May 2000\n|13\n|-\n|'''8'''\n|7 September 2000\n|6 January 2001\n|55\n|-\n|'''9'''\n|8 January 2001\n|26 April 2001\n|45\n|-\n|'''10'''\n|4 September 2001\n|29 December 2001\n|43\n|-\n|'''11'''\n|5 January 2002\n|9 April 2002\n|55\n|-\n|'''12'''\n|31 August 2002\n|28 December 2002\n|20\n|-\n|'''13'''\n|4 January 2003\n|31 May 2003\n|22\n|-\n|'''14'''\n|30 August 2003\n|27 December 2003\n|22\n|-\n|'''15'''\n|3 January 2004\n|5 June 2004\n|23\n|-\n|'''16'''\n|18 September 2004\n|25 December 2004\n|16\n|-\n|'''17'''\n|1 January 2005\n|11 June 2005\n|25\n|-\n|'''18'''\n|17 September 2005\n|31 December 2005\n|10\n|-\n|'''19'''\n|7 January 2006\n|8 July 2006\n|28\n|-\n|'''20'''\n|9 September 2006\n|6 January 2007\n|13\n|-\n|'''21'''\n|10 March 2007\n|28 July 2007\n|18\n|-\n|'''22'''\n|18 August 2007\n|30 October 2007\n|10\n|-\n|'''23'''\n|1 January 2008\n|3 June 2008\n|20\n|-\n|'''24'''\n|16 August 2008\n|31 January 2009\n|18\n|-\n|'''25'''\n|13 June 2009\n|20 December 2009\n|20\n|-\n|'''26'''\n|13 April 2010\n|8 June 2010\n|8\n|-\n|'''27'''\n|3 August 2010\n|23 December 2010\n|10\n|-\n|'''28'''\n|2 April 2011\n|19 December 2011\n|6\n|-\n|'''29'''\n|3 January 2012\n|20 December 2012\n|10\n|-\n|'''30'''\n|1 January 2013\n|11 February 2014\n|10\n|-\n|'''31'''\n|5 May 2018\n|11 May 2018\n|7\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Jeremy Clarkson]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''32'''\n| 1 January 2019\n| 6 January 2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |10\n|-\n|4 March 2019\n|8 March 2019\n|-\n|'''33'''\n|24 August 2019 \n|20 October 2019\n|10\n|-\n|'''34'''\n|25 December 2019\n|TBC 2020\n|12\n|}\n\n===Specials===\n*'''''Is that Your Final Answer?''''' \u2013 a one-hour documentary about the show, which aired on ITV on 24 December 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukchristmastv.weebly.com/itv-1999.html|title=ITV 1999|website=UK Christmas TV|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9xrMLC3tA0|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire \u2013 Is That Your Final Answer Documentary (1999)|first=|last=Coldclough|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Directed and produced by Robin Lough, it featured rare footage from the unaired pilot version of the programme, which has completely different music and behind the scenes footage from the programmes aired in Series 4 (September 1999). A similar documentary of the same name was also aired in Australia during 2000. A shorter half-hour Russian version was aired on 4 November 2000. Both of these primarily concentrated on their own versions of the show and featured the local hosts.\n*'''''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire Night''''' \u2013 a two-and-a-half-hour long special, which included parts of ''Is that Your Final Answer?'', that aired on digital channel [[ITV2]] in 2000. Hosted by Tarrant, it looked back on the first two years of the UK version, showing some of its best moments. It also looked at the original [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)|U.S.]] and [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (Australian game show)|Australian version]]s.\n*'''''Who Wants to Steal a Million?''''' \u2013 a two-hour documentary based on the [[Charles Ingram]] cheating scandal first broadcast on 9 June 2003, which features the major's full run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0370060/|title=Who Wants to Steal a Million?|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref> This was preceded by a special episode of ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'' which featured key segments of Ingram's run as well as interviews by the witnesses of the ensuing trial; the [[Martin Bashir]]-hosted documentary was broadcast on 21 April 2003 (before airing in the US on 8 May 2003 as a special episode of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Primetime (American TV program)|Primetime]]''). The documentary later aired on 15 February 2004, with subtitles, on [[HRT 2]] in Croatia. A special episode of the French version of ''Millionaire'', entitled \"''L'\u00e9mission interdite''\" (English translation: ''Prohibited episode''), was devoted to the scandal. This was broadcast on 1 July 2003 on [[TF1]].\n*'''''[[Quiz (TV series)|QUIZ]]''''' \u2013 A drama in three parts, each one hour in length, which aired on 13, 14 and 15 April 2020 and is based [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]]'s [[Quiz (TV series)|play of the same name]] which centres on the 2001 'cheating scandal'.\n\n== Text game (2004\u20132007) ==\nOn 23 October 2004 the show included a new feature called the \"Walkaway Text Game\". The competition was offered to viewers at home to play the text game where they had to answer the question, if a contestant decided to walk home with the cash prize they have got, by choosing the letters 'A, B, C or D' within 30 seconds to a specific mobile number. The viewer who answered the question won \u00a31,000 by having their entries selected randomly.\n\nOn 9 September 2006, there were some changes. The competition stayed the same but this time, they played it before some commercial breaks.  A question to which the contestant had given their final answer, but the correct answer had not yet been revealed, was offered as a competition to viewers. Entry was via [[SMS]] text message at a cost of \u00a31 per entry, and the competition ran through the commercial break, after which the answer was revealed and the game continued. One viewer who answered the question correctly won \u00a31,000. The text game ended on 28 July 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Millionaire\u2014Walkaway Game\n| publisher = itv.com\n| date =\n| url = http://millionaire.itv.com/millionaire/howtoplaywalkaway.php\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080724192629/http://millionaire.itv.com/millionaire/howtoplaywalkaway.php\n| archivedate = 24 July 2008\n| accessdate =25 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Incorrect answer to question accepted===\nOn 8 March 1999, contestant Tony Kennedy reached the \u00a364,000 question. He was asked \"Theoretically, what is the minimum number of strokes with which a [[tennis]] player can win a set?\", and given four possible answers \u2013 twelve, twenty-four, thirty-six, and forty-eight. Kennedy, who calculated that a player would need four shots to win a game, with six games in a set, answered twenty-four, and was told the answer was correct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDBNAIXmlEw&t=6m45s|title=Who Wants to be a Millionaire?  8th March 1999 Tony Kennedy|first=|last=James Booker|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the right answer was actually twelve and viewers quickly phoned up the show to complain.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/293549.stm|title=Quiz 'winner' keeps his prize|date=9 March 1999|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> One such viewer, Robert Steadman, explained to ''[[The Irish Times]]'':\n:\"A tennis player needs six games to win a set. Let's assume he serves [[Ace (tennis)|aces]] for his three service games \u2013 four shots for three games which equals 12 strokes. Now, if his opponent [[Double fault (tennis)|double faults]] all their serves \u2013 so losing love 40 \u2013 the player hasn't had to make any strokes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/man-scores-with-wrong-answer-1.160845|title=Man scores with wrong answer|date=9 March 1999|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe production staff acknowledged the mistake and apologised for it, but allowed Kennedy to keep his prize money (an eventual \u00a3125,000).<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n===Schedule rigging allegation===\nWhen [[Judith Keppel]]'s victory as the first UK jackpot winner on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' was announced by ITV on the day of that the corresponding episode was to be broadcast, several allegations were made that [[Celador]] had rigged the show to spoil the BBC's expected high ratings for the [[Things Aren't Simple Any More|finale]] of ''[[One Foot in the Grave]]''.<ref name=\"w184\">{{harvnb|Webber|2006|p=184}}</ref> [[Richard Wilson (Scottish actor)|Richard Wilson]], the lead star on the sitcom, was quoted in particular for saying that the broadcaster had \"planned\" the win, adding \"it seems a bit unfair to take the audience away from Victor's last moments on earth.\"<ref name=\"wilson\">{{cite news |title=Wilson: Millionaire win 'planned' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1035069.stm |work=BBC News |date=22 November 2000 |accessdate=28 January 2007}}</ref> [[David Renwick]], writer of the sitcom, voiced annoyance that the episode would draw away interest from the sitcom's finale, believing that a leaked press release on ITV's announcement had been \"naked opportunism\", and it \"would have been more honourable to let the show go out in the normal way\", pointing out that it \"killed off any element of tension or surprise in their own programme\", but that \"television is all about ratings\".<ref name=\"w184\"/> Richard Webber's account, in his 2006 book, cites \"unnamed BBC sources\" as those who \"questioned the authenticity of Keppel's victory\".<ref name=\"w184\"/> The allegations, in turn, led to eleven viewers making complaints against the quiz show, of a similar nature, to the [[Independent Television Commission]] (ITC).<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |title=Millionaire? cleared of ratings 'fix' |work=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1118212.stm |date=15 January 2001 |accessdate=28 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn response, ITV expressed distress to the allegations, claiming that it \"undermined viewers' faith in the programme.\" Leslie Hill, the chairman of ITV, wrote to Sir [[Christopher Bland]], the chairman of the [[Board of Governors of the BBC]], to complain about the issue. The corporation apologised, saying that any suggestion of 'rigging' \"did not represent the official view of the BBC\",<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news |first=Terri |last=Judd |title=BBC apologises for 'Millionaire' dirty tricks slur |work=The Independent |date=2 December 2000 |location=London}}</ref> while the ITC's investigation cleared the programme of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"cleared\" /><ref name=\"casey\">{{harvnb|Casey|Calvert |2008|p=128}}</ref><ref name=\"bfi\">{{harvnb|Dyja|2002|p=20}}</ref>\n\n===Ambiguous question===\nOn 11 February 2006, celebrity couple [[Laurence Llewelyn-Bowen]] and his wife Jackie took on the game show to raise money for their chosen charity \u2013 The Shooting Star Children's Hospice. Having reached the final question of the quiz, they were asked \"Translated from the Latin, what is the motto of the United States?\", to which the Bowens answered with \"[[In God We Trust|In God, We Trust]]\", only to learn that the question's correct answer was \"One Out of Many\" \u2013 the English translation for the Latin ''[[E pluribus unum]]''.<ref name=\"secondchance\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4608690.stm|title=TV designer's second shot at \u00a31m |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=13 January 2006|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> However, Celador later admitted that the question had been ambiguous and not fair to the pair \u2013 although ''E pluribus unum'' is considered the de facto motto of the United States, it was never legally declared as such; ''In God, We Trust'' is the official motto of the country since 1956, although it is not translated from any form of Latin. Following this revelation, the production company invited the Bowens back to tackle a new question, with their original winnings reinstated; the couple chose not to risk the new question, and left with \u00a3500,000 for their charity.<ref name=\"secondchance\" />\n\n===Ingram cheating scandal===\n{{further|Charles Ingram#Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|l1=Charles Ingram \u2013 Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? scandal}}\n[[File:Charles Ingram 1.jpg|thumb|Charles Ingram and his wife Diana. Both had previously made appearances on the show, before Charles' controversial game in September 2001.]]\nIn September 2001, [[Major (United Kingdom)|British Army Major]] [[Charles Ingram]] became a contestant on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', joined by his wife Diana and a college lecturer, [[Tecwen Whittock]]. After the first day of filming, the group devised a scheme that would allow Ingram to win the \u00a31&nbsp;million cash prize when he returned for the second day of recording, on 10 September \u2013 for each question he faced, the correct answer would be signalled to Ingram by a cough made by Whittock;<ref name=\"Ingram Ploy\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm |title=Major Charles Ingram has been found guilty of cheating his way to the top prize on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 April 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Ingram would differentiate the way he received this to avoid making the scheme too obvious, such as reading aloud all four answers, or dismissing an answer and then choosing it again later.<ref name=\"Ingram Ploy\" /> Although the scheme proved successful, by the time he had reached the final questions, production staff off-stage had become suspicious over the amount of background noise being made by Whittock's coughing,<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2910119.stm|title=Millionaire trio escape jail|work=BBC News|date=8 April 2003|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> while noting that Ingram seemed to show no specialist knowledge of any subjects he faced with each question.\n\nAfter the second day of recording ended, the production staff ordered an immediate investigation on the grounds that cheating had occurred, suspending the broadcast of both episodes that had been filmed. Ingram was subsequently informed that he was being investigated for cheating and would not receive his winnings. While reviewing the recording, production staff began to see a pattern between Whittock's coughing, and Ingram's unusual behaviour when he answered questions;<ref name=\"FoundGuilty\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm|title=Millionaire's route to the top prize|date=7 April 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"devastated\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2964675.stm|title=Millionaire cheats left 'devastated'|date=21 April 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> at one point, they noticed Ingram gave an answer when Diana had coughed after he read it aloud. By this point,  production company [[Celador]] was convinced that cheating had occurred, and the matter was handed over to police. Both the Ingrams and Whittock were charged with \"procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception\", and taken to [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]] [[Crown Court]] in 2003.\n\nDuring the four-week long trial, the Prosecution provided evidence towards the charges, which included a recording of Ingram's second day on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'', pager telephone records for a previous scheme the group intended to use,<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/uk/Pager-plot-too-risky-for.2408136.jp |title=Pager plot too risky for TV quiz |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=[[The Scotsman]] |first=John |last=Innes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022105328/http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/pager-plot-too-risky-for-tv-quiz-1-548871|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref> before deeming it too complicated \u2013 a system of four pagers intended to be hidden on Ingram's body, in which a pager's vibrations signalled the correct answer \u2013 and testimony from one of the production staff and a \"Fastest Finger\" contestant attending the recording, Larry Whitehurst.<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /><ref name=\"BBC News\u2013Coughs\">{{cite news|title=Contestant 'spotted Millionaire coughs'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2839587.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 July 2011|date=11 March 2003}}</ref> Although the Defence provided evidence claiming Whittock's coughing was a result of dust allergies and a hay fever he was suffering from, and Whittock himself testified against the accusations,<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weekend/story/0,3605,938649,00.html |title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part two |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 April 2003 |location=London |work=The Guardian}}</ref> the Prosecution refuted these claims with their evidence, including footage that showed Whittock stopped coughing when he became a contestant after Ingram.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> On 7 April 2003, the group were found guilty, with all three given [[suspended sentence|suspended prison sentences]] and fines, with the Ingrams later ordered to pay legal costs within two months of the trial's conclusion.<ref name=\"Ingram Trial\" /> On 24 July 2003, the British Army ordered Charles Ingram to resign his commission as a Major, in the wake of the trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3092357.stm|title=Millionaire cheat sacked by Army|date=24 July 2003|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the trial, the scandal became the subject of an ITV documentary entitled ''Millionaire: A Major Fraud'' (aired as an edition of ''[[Tonight with Trevor McDonald]]'') presented by [[Martin Bashir]] and broadcast on 21 April 2003, with a follow-up two weeks later entitled ''Millionaire: The Final Answer''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/apr/22/1|title=The cough carries it off|last=Day|first=Julian|date=22 April 2003|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> The documentary featured excerpts from the recording that had been enhanced for the Ingrams' trial, footage of the actions made by Ingram's wife in the audience, and interviews with production staff and some of the contestants who had been present during the recording. None of the defendants in the case took part, with Ingram later describing ''Major Fraud'' and a subsequent programme of the matter, shown on [[ITV2]], as \"one of the greatest TV editing con tricks in history\". Chess grandmaster [[James Plaskett]] later wrote an essay arguing in favour of the group's innocence;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://millionaire3.blogspot.com/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822075317/http://www.themillionairethree.com/|url-status=dead|title=Millionaire Three \u2013 The Rich, The Poor And Inbetween|archivedate=22 August 2012}}</ref> journalists [[Bob Woffinden]], and [[Jon Ronson]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Are the Millionaire three innocent?|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 July 2006|url=http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/jon_ronson/2006/07/could_the_who_wants_to_be_a_mi.html|accessdate=25 September 2007 |location=London |first=Jon |last=Ronson |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109152611/http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/jon_ronson/2006/07/could_the_who_wants_to_be_a_mi.html|archivedate=19 November 2007}}</ref> each wrote a piece influenced by this essay, with Woffinden collaborating with Plaskett on a book entitled ''Bad Show: The Quiz, The Cough, The Millionaire Major'', published in 2015, arguing that Ingram's appearance on the show coinciding with Whittock's was \"chance\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/552631/Coughing-cheat-Who-Wants-to-be-a-Millionaire-was-innocent|title='Coughing Major' was INNOCENT of cheating on Who Wants to be a Millionaire, says new book|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Winchester|first=Levi|date=17 January 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> A play based upon the events of the scandal was written by [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]], entitled ''[[Quiz (play)|Quiz]]'', and was performed from 3 November 2017 to 9 December 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cft.org.uk/whats-on/event/quiz |title=Quiz |accessdate=18 November 2017 |publisher=Chichester Festival Theatre}}</ref> before being performed in the West End from 31 March 2018 to 16 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412123518/http://quiztheplay.com/|title=Quiz the Play by James Graham {{!}} Official West End Website|date=12 April 2018|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>Following the success of the West End performance, Quiz, ITV commissioned a new 3 part drama based on the cheating scandal also titled 'Quiz' and written by James Graham which is set to air in the UK on  13, 14 and 15 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itvmedia.co.uk/making-an-impact/itv-has-commissioned-quiz-a-three-part-drama-directed-by-stephen-frears-starring-hollywood-star-michael-sheen|title=ITV has commissioned 'Quiz' directed by Stephen Frears starring Hollywood star, Michael Sheen|website=ITV Media|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===Phone-a-Friend===\nThe Phone-a-Friend lifeline provided multiple instances of controversy during the show's run. A 2002 edition of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' reported that many contestants had selected strangers who were \"contacts among the quizzing fraternity\"<ref>[[#Woffinden|Woffinden; Plaskett]], p.55</ref> to act as their Phone-a-Friends. Specifically, game show champion [[Daphne Fowler]] was approached by a man she had not previously met and asked if she would be his lifeline in exchange for \u00a3200. Fowler refused, adding: \"I thought a fair price would be a quarter of whatever the man won, so if I helped him get from \u00a332,000 to \u00a364,000 I would expect to get \u00a316,000.\"<ref name=\"Fowler\">{{cite news|last=Conlan|first=Tara|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-110267/Ill-phone-stranger.html|title=I'll phone a stranger|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=18 April 2002|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}} The man was later revealed by ITV sources not to have made it onto the programme.<ref name=\"Fowler\"/>\n\nIn March 2007 various UK newspapers reported that an organised syndicate had been getting quiz enthusiasts onto the show in return for a percentage of their winnings. The person behind the syndicate was Keith Burgess from Northern Ireland. Burgess admitted to helping around 200 contestants to appear on the show since 1999; he estimates those contestants to have won around \u00a35,000,000. The show producers are believed to have been aware of this operation, with Burgess stating: \"The show knows about me and these types of syndicates, but they cover it up to keep the show going.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Phoney a Friend|work=[[Sunday Mirror]]|date=18 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quiz syndicate leader denies wrongdoing|publisher=crewechronicle.co.uk|date=23 March 2007|url=http://www.crewechronicle.co.uk/news/local-news/quiz-syndicate-leader-denies-wrongdoing-5636037|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> An earlier version of a Phone a Friend syndicate was reported in the ''Northampton Chronicle and Echo'' during 2003.<ref name=\"Northampton\">{{cite news|title=Millionaire syndicate is probed|publisher=northamptonchron.co.uk|date=23 April 2003|url=http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/local/millionaire-syndicate-is-probed-1-888831|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> Paul Smith, the managing director of Celador Productions, stated: \"We are aware of Paddy Spooner and what people similar to him are doing, and we have made a priority of changing our question procedure. We are confident we have now made it impossible for anyone to manipulate the system.\"<ref name=\"Northampton\" /> Since then, the options of people that can be called have a picture of themselves shown on-air. During the 2010-14 era, and with the show's relaunch in 2018 every person listed as a friend who might be called had a person from the production company present to video their actions.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Filming locations==\nSince airing in September 1998, ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' has been filmed at 3 locations throughout its 21-year run. It was first filmed at the now-defunct [[Fountain Studios]] in London from its inception until the end of the third series which aired in March 1999. It then moved to [[Elstree Studios]], also in London, in preparation for series 4, which aired in September 1999. Elstree was the home of '' Millionaire '' right up until the end of its initial run in February 2014. For the show\u2019s revival in 2018 and all subsequent episodes, filming moved to [[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] in Manchester.\n\n*Fountain Studios \u2013 Series 1\u20133 (36 episodes)\n*Elstree Studios \u2013 Series 4\u201330 (556 episodes)\n*dock10 studios \u2013 Series 31\u2013present (32 episodes)\n\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |first1=Bernadette |last1=Casey |first2=Ben |last2=Calvert |title=Television Studies: The Key Concepts |publisher=Routledge |location=London |year=2008 |edition=2 |isbn=978-0-415-37149-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-first=Eddie |editor1-last=Dyja |title=BFI Film and Television Handbook 2002 |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London |year=2002|isbn=978-0-85170-904-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Richard |last=Webber |title=The Complete One Foot in the Grave |publisher=Orion |location=London |year=2006|isbn=978-0-7528-7357-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=Woffinden|first1=Bob|last1=Woffinden|first2=James|last2=Plaskett|title=Bad Show: The Quiz, the Cough, the Millionaire Major|publisher=Bojangles Books|year=2015|isbn=978-0-9930755-2-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.millionaire-show.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0166064|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK)}}\n* {{UKGameshow|Who_Wants_to_be_a_Millionaire%3F|Who Wants to be a Millionaire?}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? (British game show)}}\n[[Category:1998 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2000s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2010s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s British game shows]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:ITV game shows]]\n[[Category:Carlton Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Steven Knight]]\n", "name_user": "Mythlike-Cell", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who_Wants_to_Be_a_Millionaire%3F_(British_game_show)"}
{"title_page": "Faisal Farooqui", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian technology entrepreneur}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Faisal Farooqui\n| image              = Faisal Farooqui 2013.jpg\n| birth_date         = 23 April\n| education          = [[Binghamton University|Binghamton University, State University of New York]]\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur, [[CEO]], [[MouthShut.com]]\n| website            = [https://www.mouthshut.com MouthShut.com]\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Faisal I. Farooqui''' is a technology [[entrepreneur]]. Farooqui is best known as the founder and [[Chief Executive Officer]] ([[CEO]]) of [[MouthShut.com]].<ref name=\"BS1newsmaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/newsmaker-faisal-farooqui-115032601198_1.html|title=Newsmaker: Faisal Farooqui|author1=Surabhi Agarwal|date=26 March 2015|work=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref> Farooqui is an advocate of freedom of expression <ref>{{cite news|title=Interview: Victory for free-speech campaigners, says section 66A petitioner|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/interview-victory-for-free-speech-campaigners-says-section-66a-petitioner/|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=24 March 2015}}</ref> on the Internet- he challenged<ref>{{cite news|author1=Avanish Tiwary|title=Section 66A of IT Act: Entire digital ecosystem will take off from here, says MouthShut founder Faisal Farooqui|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/entire-digital-ecosystem-will-take-off-from-here-faisal-farooqui/57177/|work=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|date=25 March 2015|ref=FE Section 66A of IT Act}}</ref> India's restrictive IT Rules in the Supreme Court which resulted in the Honorable Supreme Court striking down of Section 66A and reading down of many other sections of the Information Technology Act of India [[Mouthshut.com v. Union of India]] <ref>{https://www.livemint.com/Politics/DSjZ9XsezZ4fN2GGfkWu1N/SC-seeks-govt-reply-on-PIL-challenging-powers-of-IT-Act.html</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFarooqui obtained a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in Information Systems and Finance from the [[Binghamton University|State University of New York at Binghamton]]. He was elected to the University's Faculty Senate Committee and the Student government. While there, he started writing tech-column and later became the Technology Editor of the campus newspaper, ''Pipe Dream''.<ref>https://www.binghamton.edu/alumni/news/alumni-connect/sep-2014/international-alumnus.html</ref>\n\nFarooqui worked as an intern with Morgan Stanely, New York. Upon graduation, he joined the telecom practice of American Management System (now acquired by CGI Systems), in [[Virginia]]. <ref> https://www.crunchbase.com/person/faisal-farooqui-86b6 </ref> <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051029150704/http://www.expresscomputeronline.com/20051003/technologylife02.shtml ]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2000, Farooqui launched [[MouthShut.com]].<ref name=\"BS1newsmaker\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051029150704/http://www.expresscomputeronline.com/20051003/technologylife02.shtml|title=Swades, the dotcom way - Express Computer|date=29 October 2005|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Adgully Bureau |url=http://www.adgully.com/exclusive-opinion-that-matters-mouthshut-s-faisal-farooqui-51240.html |title=Exclusive &#124; Opinion, that matters: MouthShut's Faisal Farooqui |website=Adgully.com |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref> According to the Economic Times, Farooqui pioneered auto-rickshaw advertising in India by painting the logo of MouthShut.com on the back of the hood of rickshaws in Mumbai in 2001<ref name=\"indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/News/News_By_Industry/Infotech/Internet__Telecom/Chunnu_Munnu_left_out_as_autos_load_dotcom_ads/articleshow/1795954.cms |title=The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/1055159/report-dotcoms-discover-a-new-marketing-vehicle |title=Dotcoms discover a new marketing vehicle &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2006-09-25 |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref> This was later extended to the entire country.<ref name=\"indiatimes.com\" />\n\nn 2012, [[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur Magazine]] named Farooqui among the Top Business People in India and was included in a list of Entrepreneurs who have created History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entrepreneurindia.in/uncategorized/create-history-1st-anniversary-issue/5604/|title=Create History: 1st Anniversary Issue|website=Entrepreneurindia.in|access-date=19 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809042350/http://entrepreneurindia.in/uncategorized/create-history-1st-anniversary-issue/5604/|archive-date=9 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Farooqui has also been named as a Youth Icon on India's national TV news channel (Doordarshan).{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe British High Commission in [[Delhi]] announced Farooqui among 50 Indians to its list of young leaders who have demonstrated exceptional leadership and symbolize optimism of the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Young Leaders Forum Delegation List|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243705/Young_Leaders_Forum_Delegation_List.xlsx|publisher=[[Gov.uk]]|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Net neutrality==\n{{Related|[[Mouthshut.com v. Union of India]]}}\nFarooqui has been a vocal advocate of [[net neutrality]] in India. He has argued that an open Internet is the right way to harness the huge entrepreneurial potential of India. In a CNBC TV18 Debate, he argued against the proponents of preferential Internet.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=apL942au7Jg</ref> Farooqui argued in an op-ed interview in ''Times of India'' that not having net neutrality will result in increased cost of internet access for the average consumer, less competition in the e-commerce space and a slower, more restrictive internet.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/blogs/the-interviews-blog/internet-users-represent-new-india-with-aspirations-and-they-want-net-neutrality-faisal-i-farooqui/ | title=Internet users represent new India with aspirations \u2013 and they want net neutrality: Faisal I Farooqui | date=11 May 2015 | newspaper=The Times of India | accessdate=14 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Farooqui and nine other Indian entrepreneurs, .{{cn|date=April 2020}} wrote an open letter to India's [[TRAI]] requesting, to issue clear regulations preventing telecom providers or content providers from acting as gate-keepers to a restricted Internet services instead of the open Internet.<ref>http://trai.gov.in/Comments_Data/Others/Letter_of_startup_founders.pdf</ref>{{non-primary source needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFarooqui and others also petitioned the Chief Ministers of twelve Indian states imploring them to prohibit the issuance of orders that make Internet services entirely inaccessible for a particular area. The petition was part of an effort by a group of  organizations and citizens led by SFLC.in,  a Delhi-based not-for-profit organization of which Farooqui is an governing board member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://internetdemocracy.in/media/organizations-citizens-urge-12-states-cms-to-stop-internet-shutdowns/|title=Organisations & citizens urge 12 states CMs to stop Internet shutdowns \u2013 The Internet Democracy Project|website=internetdemocracy.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.mouthshut.com/user/faisal.html Official homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farooqui, Faisal}}\n[[Category:Binghamton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian technology entrepreneur}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Faisal Farooqui\n| image              = Faisal Farooqui 2013.jpg\n| birth_date         = 23 April\n| education          = [[Binghamton University|Binghamton University, State University of New York]]\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur, [[CEO]], [[MouthShut.com]]\n| website            = [https://www.mouthshut.com MouthShut.com]\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Faisal I. Farooqui''' is a technology [[entrepreneur]]. Farooqui is best known as the founder and [[Chief Executive Officer]] ([[CEO]]) of [[MouthShut.com]].<ref name=\"BS1newsmaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/newsmaker-faisal-farooqui-115032601198_1.html|title=Newsmaker: Faisal Farooqui|author1=Surabhi Agarwal|date=26 March 2015|work=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref> Farooqui is an advocate of freedom of expression <ref>{{cite news|title=Interview: Victory for free-speech campaigners, says section 66A petitioner|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/interview-victory-for-free-speech-campaigners-says-section-66a-petitioner/|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=24 March 2015}}</ref> on the Internet- he challenged<ref>{{cite news|author1=Avanish Tiwary|title=Section 66A of IT Act: Entire digital ecosystem will take off from here, says MouthShut founder Faisal Farooqui|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/industry/entire-digital-ecosystem-will-take-off-from-here-faisal-farooqui/57177/|work=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|date=25 March 2015|ref=FE Section 66A of IT Act}}</ref> India's restrictive IT Rules in the Supreme Court which resulted in the Honorable Supreme Court striking down of Section 66A and reading down of many other sections of the Information Technology Act of India [[Mouthshut.com v. Union of India]] <ref>{https://www.livemint.com/Politics/DSjZ9XsezZ4fN2GGfkWu1N/SC-seeks-govt-reply-on-PIL-challenging-powers-of-IT-Act.html</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFarooqui obtained a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in Information Systems and Finance from the [[Binghamton University|State University of New York at Binghamton]]. He was elected to the University's Faculty Senate Committee and the Student government. While there, he started writing tech-column and later became the Technology Editor of the campus newspaper, ''Pipe Dream''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.binghamton.edu/alumni/news-and-learning/alumni-connect/index.html|title=Alumni Connect - Alumni Association &#124; Binghamton University|website=Alumni Association - Binghamton University}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2000, Farooqui launched [[MouthShut.com]].<ref name=\"BS1newsmaker\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051029150704/http://www.expresscomputeronline.com/20051003/technologylife02.shtml|title=Swades, the dotcom way - Express Computer|date=29 October 2005|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Adgully Bureau |url=http://www.adgully.com/exclusive-opinion-that-matters-mouthshut-s-faisal-farooqui-51240.html |title=Exclusive &#124; Opinion, that matters: MouthShut's Faisal Farooqui |website=Adgully.com |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref> According to the Economic Times, Farooqui pioneered auto-rickshaw advertising in India by painting the logo of MouthShut.com on the back of the hood of rickshaws in Mumbai in 2001<ref name=\"indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/News/News_By_Industry/Infotech/Internet__Telecom/Chunnu_Munnu_left_out_as_autos_load_dotcom_ads/articleshow/1795954.cms |title=The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/1055159/report-dotcoms-discover-a-new-marketing-vehicle |title=Dotcoms discover a new marketing vehicle &#124; Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis |website=Dnaindia.com |date=2006-09-25 |accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref> This was later extended to the entire country.<ref name=\"indiatimes.com\" />\n\nn 2012, [[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur Magazine]] named Farooqui among the Top Business People in India and was included in a list of Entrepreneurs who have created History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entrepreneurindia.in/uncategorized/create-history-1st-anniversary-issue/5604/|title=Create History: 1st Anniversary Issue|website=Entrepreneurindia.in|access-date=19 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809042350/http://entrepreneurindia.in/uncategorized/create-history-1st-anniversary-issue/5604/|archive-date=9 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Farooqui has also been named as a Youth Icon on India's national TV news channel (Doordarshan).{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe British High Commission in [[Delhi]] announced Farooqui among 50 Indians to its list of young leaders who have demonstrated exceptional leadership and symbolize optimism of the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Young Leaders Forum Delegation List|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243705/Young_Leaders_Forum_Delegation_List.xlsx|publisher=[[Gov.uk]]|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Net neutrality==\n{{Related|[[Mouthshut.com v. Union of India]]}}\nFarooqui has been a vocal advocate of [[net neutrality]] in India. He has argued that an open Internet is the right way to harness the huge entrepreneurial potential of India. In a CNBC TV18 Debate, he argued against the proponents of preferential Internet.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=apL942au7Jg</ref> Farooqui argued in an op-ed interview in ''Times of India'' that not having net neutrality will result in increased cost of internet access for the average consumer, less competition in the e-commerce space and a slower, more restrictive internet.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/blogs/the-interviews-blog/internet-users-represent-new-india-with-aspirations-and-they-want-net-neutrality-faisal-i-farooqui/ | title=Internet users represent new India with aspirations \u2013 and they want net neutrality: Faisal I Farooqui | date=11 May 2015 | newspaper=The Times of India | accessdate=14 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Farooqui and nine other Indian entrepreneurs, wrote an open letter to India's [[TRAI]] requesting, to issue clear regulations preventing telecom providers or content providers from acting as gate-keepers to a restricted Internet services instead of the open Internet.<ref>http://trai.gov.in/Comments_Data/Others/Letter_of_startup_founders.pdf</ref>{{non-primary source needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFarooqui and others also petitioned the Chief Ministers of twelve Indian states imploring them to prohibit the issuance of orders that make Internet services entirely inaccessible for a particular area. The petition was part of an effort by a group of  organizations and citizens led by SFLC.in,  a Delhi-based not-for-profit organization of which Farooqui is an governing board member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://internetdemocracy.in/media/organizations-citizens-urge-12-states-cms-to-stop-internet-shutdowns/|title=Organisations & citizens urge 12 states CMs to stop Internet shutdowns \u2013 The Internet Democracy Project|website=internetdemocracy.in}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.mouthshut.com/user/faisal.html Official homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farooqui, Faisal}}\n[[Category:Binghamton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in information technology]]\n", "name_user": "Cokestunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup and citation. note: a potentiol case of racist edit warring by one US based editor.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faisal_Farooqui"}
{"title_page": "Female infanticide in Pakistan", "text_new": "[[File:2012 Birth Sex Ratio World Map.jpg|thumb|200px|World map of birth sex ratios, 2012]]\n{{Violence against women}}\n'''Female infanticide in Pakistan'''  had been a common practice in the Indo-Pak Subcontinent. But it is no longer a common practice both in Pakistan and India via steps taken by local polices and Governments and Ordinances made  in both neighbours.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mariya Karimjee |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/1/14/infanticides-on-theriseinpakistan.html |title=Infanticide is on the rise in Pakistan &#124; Al Jazeera America |publisher=America.aljazeera.com |date=2014-01-14 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDuring the 19th century, the Northwest [[British raj|British India]] one-fourth of the population preserved only half the daughters, while other 3/4th of the population had balanced sex ratio. There were 118 males per 100 females. This is comparable to the late C20th sex ratio in the area, now divided between India and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|title = Child Survival: Anthropological Perspectives on the Treatment and Maltreatment of Children|last = Hughes|first = Nancy Scheper|publisher = Springer|isbn = 9781556080289|year = 1987|page = 99}}</ref>\n\nAmong [[Kharal|Kharal people]], female infanticide was common. A report from 1884 states:\n\n<blockquote>The Kharrals are the most northerly of the great [[Tribes of the Bar Region of the Punjab|Ravi tribes]], occupying a great portion of the land between [[Gogera|Gugera]] and the [[Lahore]] district on both sides of the river, and extending some distance into the [[Gujranwala District|Gujranwala district]]. The Kharrals were [[Rajput]]s... and never got on with each other. The feuds of the [[Lakhera]]s and upper Ravi Kharrals have been noticed. The tragic adventure of Mirza and Sahiban is said to have been the cause of desperate quarrels. Mirza was a Kharral of the Sahi muhin... went as a boy to [[Hast Khewa|Khewa]] in [[Jhang District|Jhang]], where he [[cousin marriage|fell in love with his cousin]] Sahiban, the daughter of the chief man of the place. Her parents betrothed her to a youth of the Chadar tribe, but before the marriage could place, Mirza ran away with her. He was pursued and slain. Her relations strangled Sahiban... These murders were cause of such bloody feuds between the clans that it at the length was thought inauspicious to have daughters, and as soon as they were born, they were strangled as Sahiban had been. This custom of female infanticide was common among the Kharrals till Colonel Hamilton, Commissioner of [[Multan District|Multan]], persuaded them to discontinue it.</blockquote><ref> ''Gazetteer of the Montgomery District''. 1884. pp 62-63</ref>\n\nThis report is cited in a 2010 book on son preference, giving the context of the [[Mirza Sahiban]] tragic romance, and putting the practice in a wider socio-economic analysis.<ref>{{cite book|title = Son Preference: Sex Selection, Gender and Culture in South Asia|last = Purewal|first = Navtej K.|isbn = 9781845204686|page = 33 |publisher = Berg}}</ref>\n\n==Son preference==\nSimilarly to other countries in [[South Asia]], Pakistani households have a strong preference for sons<ref>https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00220388.2018.1516871</ref><ref>https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02293629/document</ref><ref>http://www.niussp.org/article/son-preference-and-within-household-bargaining-position-of-pakistani-women-preference-pour-les-garcons-et-le-pouvoir-de-negociation-des-femmes-pakistanaises/</ref><ref>https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/southasia/2019/12/03/money-matters-gender-equality-and-a-babys-sex-in-pakistan/</ref>. Parent fertility remains incomplete until and unless the desired number of boys are  born<ref>https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02293629/document</ref>. Son preference prevails in rural areas, due to male inheritance of agricultural land, and males being seen as better suited to work the land. Boys are often given better access to resources, healthcare, and education. Prenatal sex-selection is more common among the upper classes who have access to medical care and technology, while abuse after birth (infanticide and abandonment) is more common among the lower classes. Girls who are unwanted are often forced into [[child marriage|early marriage]].<ref>https://www.popcouncil.org/uploads/pdfs/2015PGY_SexSelectionPakistan.pdf</ref><ref>http://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/Pnadm056.pdf</ref>. Son preference has effect on the status of Pakistani women. women bearing at least one son have higher say  in household decision-making <ref>https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00220388.2018.1516871</ref>.\n\n==Dowry==\nFamilies often do not want daughters because they are expected to pay [[dowry]] upon their marriage. The giving and expectation of a dowry is part of the culture, with most marriages in every region of Pakistan involving transfer of a dowry from the bride's family to a groom's family.<ref>[http://www.popcouncil.org/pdfs/ayp0102.pdf Zeba Sathar, Cynthia Lloyd, et al. (2001\u20132002) \"Adolescents and Youth in Pakistan\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312003405/http://www.popcouncil.org/pdfs/ayp0102.pdf |date=2014-03-12 }} pp.92-116,  Population Council (with support from UNICEF)</ref> Conflicts related to dowry often lead to violence. At over 2000 dowry-related deaths per year, and annual rates exceeding 2.45 deaths per 100,000 women from dowry-related violence, Pakistan has the highest reported number of dowry death rates per 100,000 women in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4e4213da2.pdf |title=Operational Note: Pakistan|publisher=Refworld, A United Nations initiative|date=August 2011|pages=16\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mpra.ub.uni-muenchen.de/21365/|title=To estimate an equation explaining the determinants of Dowry|publisher=|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Culture of family honor==\n{{Main|Family honor|Honor killing in Pakistan}}\nPakistan has a strong 'culture of honor', where a female can easily tarnish the 'honor' and 'reputation' of her family through certain behaviors (often related to [[chastity]]), whether these behaviors are real or suspected by the community. The ''family honor'' is an abstract concept involving the perceived quality of worthiness and respectability that affects the social standing and the self-evaluation of a group of related people, both corporately and individually.<ref name=\"Malina2001\">{{cite book|author=Bruce J. Malina|title=The New Testament world: insights from cultural anthropology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ek3fSY7jRDcC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=15 February 2001|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=978-0-664-22295-6|page=42}}</ref><ref name=\"spain\">{{cite journal|last=Mosquera|first=Patricia M. R. |author2=Antony S. R. Manstead |author3=Agneta H. Fischer|title=Honor in the Mediterranean and Northern Europe|journal=Journal of Cross-Cultural Psychology|date=January 2002|volume=33|issue=1|pages=16\u201336|url=http://jcc.sagepub.com/content/33/1/16.short|accessdate=17 October 2011|doi=10.1177/0022022102033001002}}</ref> The [[family]] is viewed as the main source of [[honor]] and the community highly values the relationship between honor and the family.<ref name=\"Family\">{{cite book |last=Berns |first=Roberta |title=Child, family, school, community: socialization and support |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AD3e7Xdn2NMC&pg=PA528&dq=family+honor+in+different+cultures#v=snippet&q=honor&f=false |year=2007 |publisher=Thompson Learning |page=139 |isbn=978-0-495-00758-6}}</ref> The conduct of family members reflects upon family honor and the way the family perceives itself, and is perceived by others.<ref name=\"spain\"/> [[Honor killings]] in Pakistan are known locally as ''karo-kari''. An honor killing is the [[homicide]] of a member of a family or social group by other members, due to the belief the victim has brought [[honour|dishonour]] upon the family or community. The death of the victim is viewed as a way to restore the reputation and honour of the family.<ref name=\"Goldstein 2002 31\">{{cite journal|last=Goldstein|first=Matthew|title=The Biological Roots of Heat-of-Passion Crimes and Honor Killings|journal=Politics and the Life Sciences|year=2002|volume=21|issue=2|page=31}}</ref>\nIn order to avoid such problems related to the honor culture, families reject altogether the idea of having daughters.<ref>https://iussp.org/sites/default/files/event_call_for_papers/generaltheoryforgenderpreference%28BUSAN201308%29.pdf</ref>\n\n==Sex selective abortion==\n[[Sex selective abortion]] - the practice of terminating a pregnancy based upon the female sex of the fetus -  is happening in Pakistan, although it is illegal.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/06/abandoned-aborted-or-left-for-dead-these-are-the-vanishing-girls-of-pakistan/258648/</ref><ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1191470</ref><ref>https://iussp.org/sites/default/files/event_call_for_papers/SRB%20Abstract%20-%20IUSSP%202013_fin.pdf</ref>\n[[Abortion]] is illegal in Pakistan, except if needed to preserve the pregnant woman' life or health.<ref> http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/pakistan.doc.</ref>\n\n==Prevalence==\n\nAccording to one estimate from the end of the 20th century, about 3.1 million girls are missing in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|title = Hardness of Heart/hardness of Life: The Stain of Human Infanticide|last = Milner|first = Larry Stephen|page = 223|publisher = University Press of America}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = Female Terror|last = Magma|first = Ann|publisher = Random House|year = 2012|isbn = 9781448132362|page = 103}}</ref> The extent to which this is attributable to infanticide is contested; see [[Missing women of Asia]].\n\nIn 1998, 391 infant girls were found dead, about 68 in 1999, 59 in 2000, 51 in 2001, and 39 in 2002.<ref>{{cite book|title = Forsaken Females: The Global Brutalization of Women|authors=Andrea Parrot, Nina Cummings|page = 65|publisher = Rowman & Littlefield|isbn = 9780742580428|year = 2006}}</ref> The number of infanticides, particularly of girls, is on the increase, according to the [[Edhi Foundation]]. They know of 890 newborns killed in 2008, 999 in 2009 and about 1,210 in 2010, and this counts only the large cities.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/105019/infanticide-on-the-rise-in-pakistan-statistics/ |title=Infanticide on the rise: 1,210 babies found dead in 2010, says Edhi \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Female infanticide in China]]\n* [[Female infanticide in India]]\n* [[Sex-selective abortion]]\n* [[Women in Pakistan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Female infanticide]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Crime in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Birth control in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sexism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Childhood in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:2012 Birth Sex Ratio World Map.jpg|thumb|200px|World map of birth sex ratios, 2012]]\n{{Violence against women}}\n'''Female infanticide in Pakistan'''  had been a common practice in the Indo-Pak Subcontinent. But it is no longer a common practice both in Pakistan and India via steps taken by local polices and Governments and Ordinances made  in both neighbours.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mariya Karimjee |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/1/14/infanticides-on-theriseinpakistan.html |title=Infanticide is on the rise in Pakistan &#124; Al Jazeera America |publisher=America.aljazeera.com |date=2014-01-14 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDuring the 19th century, the Northwest [[British raj|British India]] one-fourth of the population preserved only half the daughters, while other 3/4th of the population had balanced sex ratio. There were 118 males per 100 females. This is comparable to the late C20th sex ratio in the area, now divided between India and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|title = Child Survival: Anthropological Perspectives on the Treatment and Maltreatment of Children|last = Hughes|first = Nancy Scheper|publisher = Springer|isbn = 9781556080289|year = 1987|page = 99}}</ref>\n\nAmong [[Kharal|Kharal people]], female infanticide was common. A report from 1884 states:\n\n<blockquote>The Kharrals are the most northerly of the great [[Tribes of the Bar Region of the Punjab|Ravi tribes]], occupying a great portion of the land between [[Gogera|Gugera]] and the [[Lahore]] district on both sides of the river, and extending some distance into the [[Gujranwala District|Gujranwala district]]. The Kharrals were [[Rajput]]s... and never got on with each other. The feuds of the [[Lakhera]]s and upper Ravi Kharrals have been noticed. The tragic adventure of Mirza and Sahiban is said to have been the cause of desperate quarrels. Mirza was a Kharral of the Sahi muhin... went as a boy to [[Hast Khewa|Khewa]] in [[Jhang District|Jhang]], where he [[cousin marriage|fell in love with his cousin]] Sahiban, the daughter of the chief man of the place. Her parents betrothed her to a youth of the Chadar tribe, but before the marriage could place, Mirza ran away with her. He was pursued and slain. Her relations strangled Sahiban... These murders were cause of such bloody feuds between the clans that it at the length was thought inauspicious to have daughters, and as soon as they were born, they were strangled as Sahiban had been. This custom of female infanticide was common among the Kharrals till Colonel Hamilton, Commissioner of [[Multan District|Multan]], persuaded them to discontinue it.</blockquote><ref> ''Gazetteer of the Montgomery District''. 1884. pp 62-63</ref>\n\nThis report is cited in a 2010 book on son preference, giving the context of the [[Mirza Sahiban]] tragic romance, and putting the practice in a wider socio-economic analysis.<ref>{{cite book|title = Son Preference: Sex Selection, Gender and Culture in South Asia|last = Purewal|first = Navtej K.|isbn = 9781845204686|page = 33 |publisher = Berg}}</ref>\n\n==Son preference==\nSimilarly to other countries in [[South Asia]], Pakistani households have a strong preference for sons<ref>https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00220388.2018.1516871</ref><ref>https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02293629/document</ref><ref>http://www.niussp.org/article/son-preference-and-within-household-bargaining-position-of-pakistani-women-preference-pour-les-garcons-et-le-pouvoir-de-negociation-des-femmes-pakistanaises/</ref><ref>https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/southasia/2019/12/03/money-matters-gender-equality-and-a-babys-sex-in-pakistan/</ref>. Parent fertility remains incomplete until and unless the desired number of boys are  born<ref>https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-02293629/document</ref>. Son preference prevails in rural areas, due to male inheritance of agricultural land, and males being seen as better suited to work the land. Boys are often given better access to resources, healthcare, and education. Prenatal sex-selection is more common among the upper classes who have access to medical care and technology, while abuse after birth (infanticide and abandonment) is more common among the lower classes. Girls who are unwanted are often forced into [[child marriage|early marriage]].<ref>https://www.popcouncil.org/uploads/pdfs/2015PGY_SexSelectionPakistan.pdf</ref><ref>http://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/Pnadm056.pdf</ref>. Son preference has effect on the status of Pakistani women. women bearing at least one son have higher say  in household decision-making <ref>https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00220388.2018.1516871</ref>.\n\n==Dowry==\nFamilies often do not want daughters because they are expected to pay [[dowry]] upon their marriage. The giving and expectation of a dowry is part of the culture, with most marriages in every region of Pakistan involving transfer of a dowry from the bride's family to a groom's family.<ref>[http://www.popcouncil.org/pdfs/ayp0102.pdf Zeba Sathar, Cynthia Lloyd, et al. (2001\u20132002) \"Adolescents and Youth in Pakistan\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312003405/http://www.popcouncil.org/pdfs/ayp0102.pdf |date=2014-03-12 }} pp.92-116,  Population Council (with support from UNICEF)</ref> Conflicts related to dowry often lead to violence. At over 2000 dowry-related deaths per year, and annual rates exceeding 2.45 deaths per 100,000 women from dowry-related violence, Pakistan has the highest reported number of dowry death rates per 100,000 women in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4e4213da2.pdf |title=Operational Note: Pakistan|publisher=Refworld, A United Nations initiative|date=August 2011|pages=16\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mpra.ub.uni-muenchen.de/21365/|title=To estimate an equation explaining the determinants of Dowry|publisher=|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Culture of family honor==\n{{Main|Family honor|Honor killing in Pakistan}}\nPakistan has a strong 'culture of honor', where a female can easily tarnish the 'honor' and 'reputation' of her family through certain behaviors (often related to [[chastity]]), whether these behaviors are real or suspected by the community. The ''family honor'' is an abstract concept involving the perceived quality of worthiness and respectability that affects the social standing and the self-evaluation of a group of related people, both corporately and individually.<ref name=\"Malina2001\">{{cite book|author=Bruce J. Malina|title=The New Testament world: insights from cultural anthropology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ek3fSY7jRDcC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=15 February 2001|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=978-0-664-22295-6|page=42}}</ref><ref name=\"spain\">{{cite journal|last=Mosquera|first=Patricia M. R. |author2=Antony S. R. Manstead |author3=Agneta H. Fischer|title=Honor in the Mediterranean and Northern Europe|journal=Journal of Cross-Cultural Psychology|date=January 2002|volume=33|issue=1|pages=16\u201336|url=http://jcc.sagepub.com/content/33/1/16.short|accessdate=17 October 2011|doi=10.1177/0022022102033001002}}</ref> The [[family]] is viewed as the main source of [[honor]] and the community highly values the relationship between honor and the family.<ref name=\"Family\">{{cite book |last=Berns |first=Roberta |title=Child, family, school, community: socialization and support |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AD3e7Xdn2NMC&pg=PA528&dq=family+honor+in+different+cultures#v=snippet&q=honor&f=false |year=2007 |publisher=Thompson Learning |page=139 |isbn=978-0-495-00758-6}}</ref> The conduct of family members reflects upon family honor and the way the family perceives itself, and is perceived by others.<ref name=\"spain\"/> [[Honor killings]] in Pakistan are known locally as ''karo-kari''. An honor killing is the [[homicide]] of a member of a family or social group by other members, due to the belief the victim has brought [[honour|dishonour]] upon the family or community. The death of the victim is viewed as a way to restore the reputation and honour of the family.<ref name=\"Goldstein 2002 31\">{{cite journal|last=Goldstein|first=Matthew|title=The Biological Roots of Heat-of-Passion Crimes and Honor Killings|journal=Politics and the Life Sciences|year=2002|volume=21|issue=2|page=31}}</ref>\nIn order to avoid such problems related to the honor culture, families reject altogether the idea of having daughters.<ref>https://iussp.org/sites/default/files/event_call_for_papers/generaltheoryforgenderpreference%28BUSAN201308%29.pdf</ref>\n\n==Sex selective abortion==\n[[Sex selective abortion]] - the practice of terminating a pregnancy based upon the female sex of the fetus -  is happening in Pakistan, although it is illegal.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/06/abandoned-aborted-or-left-for-dead-these-are-the-vanishing-girls-of-pakistan/258648/</ref><ref>https://www.dawn.com/news/1191470</ref><ref>https://iussp.org/sites/default/files/event_call_for_papers/SRB%20Abstract%20-%20IUSSP%202013_fin.pdf</ref>\n[[Abortion]] is illegal in Pakistan, except if needed to preserve the pregnant woman' life or health.<ref> http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/pakistan.doc.</ref>\n\n==Prevalence==\n\nAccording to one estimate from the end of the 20th century, about 3.1 million girls are missing in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|title = Hardness of Heart/hardness of Life: The Stain of Human Infanticide|last = Milner|first = Larry Stephen|page = 223|publisher = University Press of America}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = Female Terror|last = Magma|first = Ann|publisher = Random House|year = 2012|isbn = 9781448132362|page = 103}}</ref> The extent to which this is attributable to infanticide is contested; see [[Missing women of Asia]].\n\nIn 1998, 391 infant girls were found dead, about 68 in 1999, 59 in 2000, 51 in 2001, and 39 in 2002.<ref>{{cite book|title = Forsaken Females: The Global Brutalization of Women|authors=Andrea Parrot, Nina Cummings|page = 65|publisher = Rowman & Littlefield|isbn = 9780742580428|year = 2006}}</ref> The number of infanticides, particularly of girls, is on the increase, according to the [[Edhi Foundation]]. They know of 890 newborns killed in 2008, 999 in 2009 and about 1,210 in 2010, and this counts only the large cities.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/105019/infanticide-on-the-rise-in-pakistan-statistics/ |title=Infanticide on the rise: 1,210 babies found dead in 2010, says Edhi \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Women in Pakistan]]\n*[[Female infanticide in China]]\n*[[Female infanticide in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Female infanticide]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Crime in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Birth control in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sexism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Childhood in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Koreangauteng", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Sex-selective abortion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Female_infanticide_in_Pakistan"}
{"title_page": "Marguerite B\u00e9clard d'Harcourt", "text_new": "[[File:Marguerite B\u00e9clard d'Harcourt 1930.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''Marguerite B\u00e9clard d'Harcourt''' (24 February 1884  - 2 August 1964) was a [[French people|French]] composer and ethno-musicologist. She was born in [[Paris]] and studied composition at the Schola Cantorum with [[Abel Decaux]], [[Vincent d'Indy]] and [[Maurice Emmanuel]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=Marguerite+B%C3%A9clard+d'Harcourt+(1884%E2%80%931964)&source=bl&ots=iHytzPKyr8&sig=LmoFioJaLVc9g1r1Sy0_Iw51JiA&hl=en&ei=fQ0_TeuUH43VgAfP-7DeCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCkQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref> \n \nShe married ethnologist Raoul d'Harcourt and afterward researched South American and Canadian<ref>{{cite book |title=Recent researches in American music|first=Victoria Lindsay|last=Levine|publisher=American Musicological Society|year=1977}}</ref> folk music, publishing texts in collaboration with him. She also collected and published folk melodies from [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]], [[Bolivia]] and other countries in standard [[Europe]]an notation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Flute music by women composers: an annotated catalog|author=Boenke, Heidi M.|year=1988}}</ref> She died in Paris.\n\n==Works==\nSelected works include:\n*''Fifty popular Indian Melodies'', 1923\n*''Raimi, or the Feast of the sun'', ballet, 1926\n*''3 Sonnets from the Renaissance'', 1930\n*''String Quartet'', 1930\n*''Three symphonic movements'', 1932\n*''Children in the pen'', melodies, 1934\u20131935\n*''Twenty-four Folk Songs of Old Quebec'', 1936\n*''Sonata Three'', 1938\n*''Dierdane'', lyric drama, 1937\u20131941\n*''Sonatine'' for flute and piano, 1946\n*''The Seasons'', 2nd symphony, 1951\u20131952\n\nWritings with Raoul d'Harcourt include:\n*''Music of the Incas and its survivals'', Paris, P. Geuthner, 1925\n*''French folk songs of Canada: their musical languag''e, Paris, PUF, 1956\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harcourt, Marguerite Beclard d}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:French music educators]]\n[[Category:Female classical composers]]\n[[Category:French classical composers]]\n[[Category:French female classical composers]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Vincent d'Indy]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Ethnomusicologists]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Maurice Emmanuel]]\n[[Category:Schola Cantorum de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century French composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century musicologists]]\n[[Category:Women music educators]]\n[[Category:Women anthropologists]]\n\n\n{{France-composer-stub}}\n{{musicologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Marguerite B\u00e9clard d'Harcourt 1930.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''Marguerite B\u00e9clard d'Harcourt''' (24 February 1884  - 2 August 1964) was a [[French people|French]] composer and ethno-musicologist. She was born in [[Paris]] and studied composition at the Schola Cantorum with [[Abel Decaux]], [[Vincent d'Indy]] and [[Maurice Emmanuel]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=Marguerite+B%C3%A9clard+d'Harcourt+(1884%E2%80%931964)&source=bl&ots=iHytzPKyr8&sig=LmoFioJaLVc9g1r1Sy0_Iw51JiA&hl=en&ei=fQ0_TeuUH43VgAfP-7DeCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCkQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref> \n \nShe married ethnologist [[Raoul d'Harcourt]] and afterward researched South American and Canadian<ref>{{cite book |title=Recent researches in American music|first=Victoria Lindsay|last=Levine|publisher=American Musicological Society|year=1977}}</ref> folk music, publishing texts in collaboration with him. She also collected and published folk melodies from [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]], [[Bolivia]] and other countries in standard [[Europe]]an notation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Flute music by women composers: an annotated catalog|author=Boenke, Heidi M.|year=1988}}</ref> She died in Paris.\n\n==Works==\nSelected works include:\n*''Fifty popular Indian Melodies'', 1923\n*''Raimi, or the Feast of the sun'', ballet, 1926\n*''3 Sonnets from the Renaissance'', 1930\n*''String Quartet'', 1930\n*''Three symphonic movements'', 1932\n*''Children in the pen'', melodies, 1934\u20131935\n*''Twenty-four Folk Songs of Old Quebec'', 1936\n*''Sonata Three'', 1938\n*''Dierdane'', lyric drama, 1937\u20131941\n*''Sonatine'' for flute and piano, 1946\n*''The Seasons'', 2nd symphony, 1951\u20131952\n\nWritings with Raoul d'Harcourt include:\n*''Music of the Incas and its survivals'', Paris, P. Geuthner, 1925\n*''French folk songs of Canada: their musical languag''e, Paris, PUF, 1956\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harcourt, Marguerite Beclard d}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:French music educators]]\n[[Category:Female classical composers]]\n[[Category:French classical composers]]\n[[Category:French female classical composers]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Vincent d'Indy]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Ethnomusicologists]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Maurice Emmanuel]]\n[[Category:Schola Cantorum de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century French composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century musicologists]]\n[[Category:Women music educators]]\n[[Category:Women anthropologists]]\n\n\n{{France-composer-stub}}\n{{musicologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "